animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bacall (GA) is a spayed 2 year old female Labrador Retriever mix rescued in Georgia from a neglectful life where she was living strictly outside with many other dogs. She had no human contact and never heard a kind word or felt a gentle touch. Bacall is a sweet pup, but she is a bit overwhelmed at all that her new life has to offer. For that reason, Bacall needs a kind, patient forever family who will give her a quiet, safe environment and the space and time she needs to adjust. Her forever home must have a fenced yard. She likes other dogs but is pretty much a 'velcro' dog with her humans, always wanting to be near them. At this time, we believe a home without young children would be best for Bacall. If you have it in your heart to lead and support Bacall in her journey to a happy life, please apply online to adopt Bacall (GA) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description: Teddy, an approx 1 year old red pitbull mix is looking for his forever home. He was neutered and vetted yesterday. He walks pretty well on a leash but he is a strong guy who hasn't learned all of his manners yet. He was raised with kids but probably older kids would be best as Teddy has a lot of energy and is very rambunctious. An active home would be great for him. He will need training as he really never got any..he was just left to his own devices and that just leads to an unruly dog. He is slowly learning that he doesn't get to do whatever he wants here but that will need to continue to be reinforced. He has been around other dogs, was raised with them but would probably do best with dogs his size or larger. He can be food aggressive but was very skinny when he came to us so resource guarding became important to him so that he wouldn't starve. He does understand that he must wait when being fed, if you make him wait before feeding. He has no food aggression towards people that we have seen, only other dogs. This should be able to be overcome with regular meals and getting him over feeling that he needs to guard his food or starve to death. Feeding separately is also an option. We do not know how Teddy does with cats. As far as we know, he has had zero experience with cats.He would probably chase them so a home without cats is recommended. With patience and consistency,  Teddy will make an awesome companion. He is a young guy with lots of potential!! Teddy's adoption fee will be $175.00 and will help to cover his neuter, vetting and cost of care while with us. If interested in giving Teddy his forever home, please complete our adoption application and email your interest. You may also text ONLY to 352-215-3260 (phone calls will not be answered or returned from this number), FB message us or call 352-493-1255(please leave a message at this number if no answer. Text, email or FB message is best for quickest response.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Hi, my name is Rango! More information on me coming soon.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $345. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

animal.description:
********************************************************************************************
Chocolate is a 6yo BLACK lab mix weighing in at 80lbs with a huge blockhead. Based on the size of his head we think he's a mix with mastiff, but his body is normal size as a Labrador.   He came to us after living his entire life on a chain outside.  He's doing great in his foster home getting all the attention. He does ok with  other dogs, prefers to be the only dog in the home. And no  cats.  He needs a quieter home with maybe someone who works from home and older kids. .  He loves his walks, but pretty chilled.  He's a cuddler and loves his humans.  He takes treats nicely and free feeds.  He rides nicely in a car. From the pictures you can see his colorful belly bands. Since he's been outside his entire life potty training took a little longer, but now he's doing well.  His tail appears half the length of a normal tail so we assume some type of previous injury. He's a good boy looking for his forever home. Chocolate is fostered in Crystal, MI.

If you are interested in meeting and possibly adopting any of our dogs, please visit https://3clr.org/adoption-process to read through our process and requirements.Adoption Fee: $350, which includes spay/neuter, age-appropriate vaccinations, up-to-date monthly heartworm preventative and microchip with lifetime enrollment. One of our volunteers will send you an application to fill out.

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Max (of Princess, Missy, and Max)! More pictures and video to come!

Max is 2 years old (approx. DOB tbd), male, 58 lbs., vetted, is or will be neutered, and micro-chipped. Max was living life on a chain and was a product of a relationship parting along with Missy and Princess.

IN HIS CURRENT DAYCARE/BOARDING ENVIRONMENT (we make no guarantees starting over in a new dynamic):

Good with Dogs? Yes

Good with Cats? NO

Has a prey drive? Yes

Good with smaller kids (mouthy, nippy, jumpy, chase, scared)? 5+ due to prey drive

Energy Level (low, low-medium, medium, medium-high, or high)? Medium+

Scared of people or socially outgoing? Outgoing

Needs another dog in the home (if scared of people), ok as only, or either way? Either way

Crate trained? Kennel trained

Does he like the crate? Yes

Potty trained? Clean in kennel

Chewer/destructive? No, but likes chew bones/chew toys in kennel

Separation Anxiety from people when left alone? No

Vocal? No very quiet

Behavior on leash when walking near lots of people/dogs? Ok

Concerning behavior: No

Best in the busy City or rural calm or doesn't matter? Doesn't matter

Stay tuned for more information as Max is a new rescue!

If you are interested in adopting Max please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out his Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
Roo  Roo  Roo

The story of Roo is a long one.  This poor guy has been bounced around and had lots of ups and downs.  Unfortunately more downs than ups.

He was picked up as a stray in Laurinburg with a leg that had a bad old injury.  The leg just hung limp. But he was just the sweetest boy ever.  No one wanted to take this on from a rescue standpoint.  Humane Society of Union County agreed to take him in and get him the care he needed.  Once he visited our vet it was recommended he have his leg amputated. He had a rough surgery due to the fact the leg had been broken and healed in the wrong position.  He made it through the surgery and rehabbed with the vet that did the surgery.  He did great!

After he healed we took him to several adoption events.  He did good at the events.  He found his FUREVER home.....well, that turned out not to work out.  Roo became to attached to his new owner.  This was a single lady.  

She was having a hard time with him being to protective.  We took him back and he returned just as happy and sweet as ever.  Maybe he wasn't in the best spot for him.  He needs a home with a leader that will keep him calm and focused.  We are offering a trainer to go along with the new owners to get him acclimated and get the right start. 

If you would like to met him please complete a non binding application at HSUC.ORG and we will get right back to you.  Thank you so much for considering giving this very sweet boy a home!!!
animal.name: Roo

animal.description:
So often people look at photos of rescue dogs listed on shelter pages and say "Hey, I think that is the dog for me"!  And that is fine with the average dog. But we would really like you to look beyond Silas's gorgeous looks and read his bio thoroughly. It is important to us, and to the person who rescued him, to make sure he gets the perfect home for his specific needs.

You see, Silas was found as a stray after roaming a neighborhood for over 2 weeks. Maybe his owner allowed him to roam, or maybe he escaped a fenced yard. We just don't know. But we would like to make sure that his new owner either has a securely fenced yard (at least 5' high) or plans to give Silas a good deal of exercise on leash every day (maybe someone who wants a running partner or wants to add a dog to their daily walk). We will not hand him over to someone who plans to tie him in the yard or allow him to just run free.

Next on the list of "must haves" is a house, not an apartment, that is located a good distance from the neighbors. This is because Silas doesn't bark, or at least he doesn't bark in the way you would generally think of. When Silas vocalizes it is more like a high pitched scream. It is kind of funny, but neighbors likely wouldn't find that to be the case.

We notice he makes the sounds mainly when he can't be with his people, and while we don't know for sure, we suspect it might be a bit of separation anxiety. So a home where someone is home often would be the best option. He definitely is not a dog that can be tied or kenneled in a yard without alarming the neighborhood.

Silas's adopter will need to be prepared to go through training the basics. He will need to learn all the common commands such as "Stay", "Down" and "Come". "Heel" would be a nice bonus as well.  He already knows "Sit" and is VERY food motivated so training will be a breeze.  He takes treats so gently!  It would be great if his adopter could take Silas to local training classes. This can be fun for both the owner and the dog and it helps form a bond that will last a lifetime!

Now that the 'Must Haves' have been established we will tell you a bit more about this handsome fellow. Silas is about 4-1/2 years old. He has a very striking look, with a white head on a blue body. His ears are the cutest, standing up straight and tipping ever so slightly at the top. Silas just LOVES attention, never passing up a belly rub. We suspect that he is housebroken but do not know if he is crate trained.

Silas is about 50 pounds which is a nice size. But typical of his breed, that 50 lbs is all muscle and he tends to pull a lot on leash. We would recommend the use of a Gentle Leader Easy walk harness (it latches in the front). We all know it is no fun walking a dog that pulls, but there are plenty of great collar and harness options that could be employed to help with this.

Silas most definitely can not live with cats. There is no easier way to put it. A cat and Silas would not make good housemates! He is not aggressive with other dogs, however, he has a very overwhelming personality with other dogs and they often don't like it. Have you ever been in the presence of someone obnoxious and you couldn't wait to leave the room? Well this is the way other dogs sometimes feel about Silas. It may be his vocalizing or maybe he is a little too 'in your face' for some dogs. Whatever it is we feel he would likely do best as an only dog in his new home.

We have found Silas to be good with children but he would likely be too much for younger kids. He is built like a brick and is as bouncy as a rabbit so children over the age of 10 would be recommended.

Now that you know what we would love to see for this sweet boy we can assure you that he is a sweet and loving soul who just needs the guidance he lacked in his early life. We just love him and know he is a diamond in the rough. Once polished he will shine so bright!

PLEASE NOTE:    DO NOT CALL THE SHELTER!!!   
If you have questions please EMAIL:  HSPCdogs@gmail.com   
We are open for adoptions Thursday - Saturday from 12-4pm (excluding holidays).  Adoptions are on a first come, first serve basis.  Adoption fee is $100 (cash or check only, NO credit cards).   Meet and greets with kids and other dogs are required.

animal.description:
1 and a half years old. 53 lbs. Female yellow labrador mix. House trained. An affectionate girl who thinks she's a lap dog! Vanilla was turned in to us from a home; the reason was that she had too much energy for their small property. She lived with children who took her for walks. Her family said she is generally well behaved, but sometimes she can get too excited. She may chew things when left alone, and she can jump fences.

She was the only dog in the home, though she did well when meeting dogs at the vet or on walks.
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Princess (of Princess, Missy, and Max)! Here is her video in NC:

https://youtu.be/nYEsb-AtfFo

Princess is 2 1/2 years old (approx. DOB tbd), female, 67 lbs., vetted, is or will be spayed, and micro-chipped. Princess was living life on a chain and was a product of a relationship parting along with Missy and Max.

IN HER CURRENT DAYCARE/BOARDING ENVIRONMENT (we make no guarantees starting over in a new dynamic):

Good with Dogs? Yes

Good with Cats? NO

Has a prey drive? Yes

Good with smaller kids (mouthy, nippy, jumpy, chase, scared)? Should be ok w kids

Energy Level (low, low-medium, medium, medium-high, or high)? Medium+

Scared of people or socially outgoing? Outgoing

Needs another dog in the home (if scared of people), ok as only, or either way? Either way

Crate trained? Yes

Does she like the crate? Yes

Potty trained? Clean in Kennel

Separation Anxiety from people when left alone? No

Vocal? When excited

Behavior on leash when walking near lots of people/dogs? Ok

Concerning behavior: None - nice dog, beautiful, white as snow

Best in the busy City or rural calm or doesn't matter? Fine either way

Stay tuned for more information as Princess is a new rescue!

If you are interested in adopting Princess please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out her Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
Dakota is a very loving dog, who hit a rough patch when a family blended and she was no longer the "spoiled baby" and center of attention.  She is fostering with other dogs but typically does not play with them. Don't think she learned how yet.

Very intelligent, very stubborn, medium to high energy,  Was trained with a training collar and some improper use of it by newcomers to her world. Now being trained with positive reinforcement and learning she won't get hurt. She's responding well so far. More details to any serious prospective candidates that have experience and a calm environment.

Does have a loud voice (typically barks not bays) when she wants something and would not be a good apartment dog.   High prey drive and will rid your yard of any critters or cats.  Thin build like a doberman (Greyhound?) but strong and likes to drag her walker. Working on that next!

She is going on 2 years old. Pictures will follow soon. She's black with tan. Ideal weight around 55 pounds.

Spayed and vaccinated.

Not recommended with small or timid children at this time. She is "scary" with her barking when she's upset but we have been concentrating on that and she is improving greatly. She has not bitten but is intimidating until you get to know her. (Great against intruders though!!).

Please email petangels@gmail.com or text 7346457705 if you might be a good fit to help her continue learning to love again.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: High prey drive so no small animals or cats.  Is currently living with a bossy Chihuahua and a dominant large breed and is adapting and learning. She is trainable but still crated when not supervised.

animal.description:
Meet Rufus!

Rufus is a character and anyone that meets him is bound to love him!  If you want some laughter in your life you will love this one.   He is a SUPER playful and spunky pup.  He loves to play with other dogs, toys and the people in his foster home.  The foster has a lot of great stories about this goofy dude to share in the short time they have had him already.

Here is a video of him from day one in their home playing with one of the kids in the foster home: https://youtu.be/HP1u-NsEEA0     

He is a very friendly dog.  Great with other dogs.  So if you are looking for a buddy for your current dog he is a contender.  Walks well on a leash.  Foster hasn't heard him bark yet.   
He demands attention! lol!  He will rub his face up against you and put his paws on you asking for pets.  

He is an active and fun dog.  If you would like a running buddy he would enjoy runs.  If you are not a runner he would enjoy daily walks and trips to the local dog park so he can get his zoomies out.  

You can see from the pictures he does have a little cute crooked face.  Unsure of what happened, but it does give him character.

He was pulled from a local rural shelter in the Houston area by one of our rescue partners so we don't have much background history on him.

He is now here with a foster in Dyer, IN and is looking for a home of his own.

We are guessing he is a young adult - 1 or 2 yrs old, 75lbs, neutered, up to date on vaccines and rabies.

Adoption Process:

- please fill out our adoption application: https://www.dayofthedogs.org/adoption-application

- one of our team members will get back to you. 

- our dogs can be seen by appointment only after an approved application has been received.

- Adoption fee helps to cover his neuter, initial vaccines, rabies, initial worming, and microchip.

-We cannot place holds on our dogs. Please do not contact us until you are prepared to adopt.

NOTE:  We are very good about updating the pet's profiles once adopted.  So no need to write us to ask "Is he/she still available?"  If the post is up, the dog is still available. 

About Us:
Day of the Dogs is a 501c3 nonprofit that is dedicated to helping shelters increase live release.  We coordinate 2 - 4 transports per month from TX, OK and AR to NW Indiana/Chicagoland area.  We do direct adoptions ourselves out of Dyer, IN area and partner with 12 other rescues and shelters in both IL and IN that are willing to help southern pets in need.   
We rely on donations to help fund our ongoing transports.  Please donate if you can.  Every dollar adds up and we are grateful for any help we can get: https://www.paypal.com/paypalme/DayoftheDogs

animal.description: Meet Wesley (aka: Paki).  Wesley is a 3 year old male Shepherd/Collie/??  mix.  Wesley came from an overcrowded shelter.  He is a medium sized dog at about 35 pounds and is full grown.  He is an absolute love bug and wants to be with his human(s) and make them proud of him.  Wesley is extremely smart and loves learning new things.  He is learning to play with the other dogs in the foster home as well as learning what toys and treats are all about.  However, his absolute favorite thing in the world is to be close to his family.  Wesley is learning some basic commands such as sit, down, wait, off, crate, etc.  Wesley loves to be out in the fully fenced back yard, playing in the snow.  He is OK playing in the yard by himself but really enjoys having one of the resident dogs or a human outside with him.  Wesley still has a lot of young dog energy and has a habit of jumping up to greet people and give them a hug (literally hugs people around the waist).  The foster is working with Wesley to train this as a command, and that he is to sit and wait for people to pet him (as opposed to him jumping up on them) - he’s really catching on to this well.  Wesley is crate trained for a full 8 hour work day, and is reliably housebroken once he learns the routine in his home and where he’s supposed to go outside. Although Wesley will go into his crate willingly, and is OK in his crate, it’s not his favorite place to be and he will bark when he hears noises so he would not be suited for an environment with shared walls / ceilings / floors as he does bark periodically throughout the day when he hears things outside.  Wesley is a bit nervous in new environments and also gets excited to see his human(s) when they come home. Given the fact that Wesley is an active dog, a fully fenced yard will be a requirement for his forever family.  Wesley has been great with all humans and dogs he has met.  Given his energetic personality and that he still jumps to greet people occasionally, a home without young children or individuals unsteady on their feet will be best.  We expect children approximately 8 years of age and up will be OK.  Wesley would do well in a home with another playful dog, and would also do well as an only dog as long as his forever family is familiar with shy dogs and their socialization needs.  Wesley is extremely smart and wants to make his humans proud of him so obedience class would be a great way to build his confidence and build a lasting bond with his family.  Wesley was heartworm positive on intake and has completed his treatment for this.  He will need to remain on oral heartworm medication and will need a follow up heartworm test in May 2021, which will be free of charge if completed at Life Care Animal Hospital.  Wesley is current on his rabies and distemper vaccinations and his microchip is registered to Second Chance.  Wesley is a sweet dog who has so much love to give to his forever family.  The adoption fee for him is $395.   If you would like to learn more about Wesley, please contact us at 651-771-5662. Remember……. adopter must have a secure fenced yard and not live in an apartment or condo.

Fill out an application http://rescuedogvillage.com/forms/RDV/frm_adopt-rdv-cp.html to be considered as a potential forever home through our rescue. PLEASE NOTE APPLICATION: you will need to type the address in the address bar because DOG NAME : KATE RDV 937 DOG GENDER: Female AGE: 3 Years Old WEIGHT: 85 Pounds BREED: German Shepherd LOCATION: Alabama Gulf Coast ADOPTION FEE: $550.00 (includes transport) EMAIL: For more information about this dog, contact email : ausman@gulftel.com EMAIL: For more information about this dog, contact: RescueDogVillage@yahoo.com APPLICATION: If this dog has stolen your heart, don't wait! Please apply online now to be considered as a potential adopter. PLEASE NOTE: All the information about this dog is in the bio. If you have not summited an application and are waiting for a response from us by email, please understand that applications are coming in every day and are being processed ahead of you. Therefore, the longer you wait for questions to be answered, the less your chances are. In addition, as home life and rescue put the needs of our rescue dogs first, we regret that we were not able to get back to you. LEASH, BASIC COMMAND AND HOUSE TRAINED SPAYED, FULLY VETTED AND CHIPPED LONG COAT/BLACK AND TAN GREAT WITH OTHER DOGS GREAT WITH PEOPLE She is big, she is bold, and she gorgeous and her name is "Kate, a three year old, knockout specimen of the German shepherd breed. Lady Kate is a classic "momma" dog, she is loving, she is loyal, she is situation aware, and she has manners and make no mistake bad behavior will not be tolerated. This girl is great at training other dogs on the rules of acceptable behavior, they seem to understand that if "momma" is not happy no one will be happy. That said Kate is playful, happy, settled, aware and scary smart! There is very little that this girl could not be trained to do. Needless to say she handled our socialization and training programs with ease, reflecting strong people drive, strong training drive, great social skills, off the scale intelligence and super situational awareness. Kate is a family style shepherd, loves children, loves and has a no miss ability protect as needed. Our girl is custom cut to be a perfect fit to a family that has the experience with the breed to appreciate her abilities. About Our Rescue Whether you adopt through Rescue Dog Village Guardian, Inc A 5013c Non-Profit Organization or any other similar organization, the LEAST we can do is thank you from the bottom of our hearts for considering welcoming these deserving dogs into your hearts and home. One of our favorite sayings is "RESCUE IS THE BEST BREED," and we believe that wholeheartedly. Help us help these dogs and submit your application today! We appreciate that you want to help make a difference in the lives of dogs who need us most!!! RESCUE ROCKS! Disclaimer: Please note that the breeds posted on our dogs' biographies are our best guess based on years of working with rescue dogs. Adopters who need to know the exact breed or mix of breeds of a particular dog must have the dog's DNA tested at their own expense.
To see more photos of this dog and all our adoptable dogs,
please check out our website at Rescue Dog Village.
RESCUE DOG VILLAGE GUARDIAN, INC A 5013C NON-PROFIT ORGAINZATION WEBSITE: WWW.RESCUEDOGVILLAGE.COM OUR DOGS ARE MICRO-CHIPPED AND READY TO BE PART OF YOUR FAMILY TODAY! These dogs deserve all of our attention, and in Rescue Dog Village Guardian, Inc A 5013c Non-Profit Organization, we are committed to our adopters and our dogs equally. We offer full disclosure and hope to make the best matches possible. Please know our adoption fees never cover our expenses. We rely on the generosity of our adopters and supporters to help us help the dogs. Our rescue is only in the business of offering full disclosure to adopters, and expects and hopes to engage your questions and concerns fully. We owe it to the dogs we rescue and all the wonderful families/adopters who might consider welcoming our charges into their hearts and home. Our dogs are waiting for that ideal forever home where they will be cherished as deserving family members. It's sad these second chances are even necessary for these dogs, but we are committed to them and will devote the time and energy to their re-homing, and not just move them to save more dogs. We diligently and responsibly seek good matches, as we don't want to re-home the dog again. These animals have already endured more than they should have, and through no fault of their own. It behooves us to be honest and forthright, and we appreciate the same in return from applicants. It's that winning combination of reciprocal trust and respect that allows for successful placements to be made. Happy adopters translate to happy dogs, and that's our goal!

animal.description:
Don't let Tank's sad pouty face fool you. He just uses it to get treats! 

He's a happy, affectionate pup who adores humans, and is game for car rides, playing, cuddling (on your lap if you'll let him), snacking, and just being with his people. He's also a fan of toys, treats and bones. 

Tank is housetrained and a perfect gentleman when left alone in the home when his humans are gone. He doesn't even require a crate! He will greet you upon your return with full-body wiggles and even the cutest "ah-ROOOO" when he's especially excited. Tank is a very laid back, and some would say lazy, pooch, but he does get the pit bull zoomies on occasion. He's pretty darned irresistible, really. 

Tank is very in tune with his humans' emotions and loves to wiggle with you when you celebrate, or snuggle you all day when you're not feeling well.  

Tank gets along great with kids, but he's a door dasher so would be best in a home with older or no kids so that he doesn't escape through a door inadvertently left ajar. Tank prefers to be the only dog in your home. 

His family loves him so much, but they have health issues and can no longer care for him. They're heartbroken to come to the conclusion that finding him a new home is what's best for Tank. 

Please text or call The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 for more info on this sweet, silly boy. He's in the Kansas City metro, but transport is available to the right home. 

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center in Shawnee, Kansas.

FOSTER & DONATIONS are urgently needed for CHEVI!!! We rescued this sweet girl from being euthanized at a vet's office by her owner. The reasons were unclear. We got a call asking if we could save her. Because this was an emergency, we took her immediately and brought her to boarding at CARL (No open foster homes).
Chevi is a super sweet, affectionate girl who gives lots of kisses! She even loves to sit against you or kind of on your lap, if she can, lol... Chevi is a little scared of some men, although she has loved the male vets and male vet techs she has met!
Chevi is only 3 1/2 years old, and is a beautiful girl. Unfortunately, we have noticed that she is having pain walking, and that she has been limping more and more, and not wanting to walk. We just got her in for an orthopedic exam and consult, and found out that she has ACL tears in both legs and needs bilateral TPLO surgery. We URGENTLY need to raise $10,000 to cover her surgery and pre-surgery tests and meds. We already have Chevi on several pain meds, joint support, CBD, fish oil, and Adequan injections, so her medical bills have been mounting fast.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Spot! I'm an older guy, maybe about 12 - but that's just a guess. I love to eat & sleep! I smile when I sleep, as you can see from one of my photos. I love to sleep in in the mornings & to take my time doing things. So if you like to take your time in the mornings, I might be the perfect buddy for you! I really enjoy being outside, so a home with a fenced yard would be fantastic! But it's not necessary.  I walk great on a leash  & I love walks! I also love to play with my blankie & to roll around on my back! I'm ADORABLE when I do that! I really need a home with no steps (or just 2 or 3 to get outside) since I'm partially blind & I become afraid. It's very hard having to go to a new home & being older & not being able to see much. I ride great in a car. Just secure me to the back seat, & I'll just enjoy the ride. I belonged to a person who had to go into a nursing home & I was going to be euthanized, but this kind woman offered to take me. She thinks I probably lived outdoors. She was able to teach me house manners & I made great progress on housetraining. (I poop outside!) But I still need some work. I'm in a temporary foster home with other dogs & a cat, & children as young as 8 years & I do fine with everyone. But my foster home has stairs, & I really need a home with no steps (or just a few). Occasionally I will randomly bark, but that is decreasing the more familiar I become with my foster home.  I become with So I need a long-term/permanent foster home or an adoptive home. animal.description:
Boxer lovers, we have a mix for you that will have your heart and head spinning. A mix between boxer and the Little Rascal's dog, Kammie is a sweet and gentle soul who just arrived at the farm quiet as a mouse and is building her confidence daily, venturing into dog fun and pets and schmoozing with the volunteers, quickly become a fav on the farm. Kammie is definitely a mix, at about a year or so old, Kammie weighs around 45 lbs full grown. Kammie would love to move into a home with another dog as she is still unsure of lots of things and does well with the guidance of doggo friends. That being said, she also really loves attention being showered on her and would also do well with folks who have patience while she settles in as well as some interest in confidence-building activities like training.
She has shown some interest in stuffed toys, and we
think once she gets more confident, she would love to play!

She's an incredibly sweet and gentle girl with good house manners.

Her favorite things to do are nap and watch TV, and she loves treats! At bedtime she will go right in her crate and not make a peep.
Kammie is ready to move onto a life in quiet suburbia that involves all of the niceties and luxuries she has yet to have experienced. There is a big world of wonderful out there and she is ready for it!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Meet Theo! He is a sweet boy who is looking for a home with adults only. He would love a home that is active and can provide lots of exercise. He is not dog friendly and would do better in a home that is in a rural setting where there is not many dogs, small animals walking around. He would love a home with big yard that he can run around in and be silly! He loves to go in the car and will try to make his way up to front seat to sit next to you! He needs owners who have had lots of experience with dogs as he does have some quirks to him, but with the right home, training and confidence, he will make an amazing new addition to your family! He is allergic to some food and currently only eating a specific brand, we ask that if you adopt him to please keep him on that food. He has been taking medicated baths every 3 days and it helps with his allergies as well. He doesn't like to be left alone, so preferably a retired couple or a home where someone is always home will be best for him. 



Foster notes: 
Theo is curious and loves to cuddle and play with humans. He also likes to sleep in the room with his people, and if you allow him on the bed, he gradually will take over it, cuddling closer and closer. 
Theo is the kind of dog who will notice when we're working long hours without moving and ask us to take a break and play with him - by pushing his nose under our elbow.
His favorite games generally involve running all over the place. He doesn't play fetch, but he runs with us around our backyard. Theo sprints back and forth. He also likes to pull on a thick rope while we hold the other end.
When he gets very excited, he runs to the living room, jumps on the couch, jumps off of it from the other and sprints back around the coffee table to jump on again. He can spend several minutes in total excitement running in a circle like this.

He gets anxious around other dogs and chases cats and squirrels. In a new home, we'd suggest avoiding other dogs and give Theo treats when dogs are in his proximity, say "yes! when giving the treat. With this approach, 95+% of the time he will be fine with the other dog passing by.

We have seen significant improvement in his behavior (which primarily was separation anxiety and aggression towards other dogs), which our friends and family have also noticed and are able to share with you. We have not seen resource guarding issues at all in over two years, and have been able to take him on hikes and trips all over California. Occasionally, we introduced him to dogs in our neighborhood and were able to have another dog with him on his walks. He has been calm and affectionate, sensitive, smart, and happy.

We have been working with a trainer recommended by the Milo Foundation to gradually address his issues. We've also met with a dog behaviorist.
Commands Theo knows: "Leave it", "Yes" "No", "Off", "Come", "Go away", "Out", "Up, "Down", "Sit", "Touch". He also responds well to descriptions of what's about to happen (e.g. "we're going to brush your teeth) and shows a general interest in communicating and listening to us. Even if he doesn't understand, he'll make an effort to interact.

Apply today to meet this amazing fellow. Adult only home with experienced owners

animal.description:
Daisy / F / 6 yrs / 80 lbs / Mastiff Shepherd Mix / Toronto

Meet Daisy! Daisy is described as a sweet and gentle girl who despite her size, is a total lush. She is loyal, eager to please, and more than ready for the right family to expose her full potential. Daisy has not always had the community of people currently advocating for her success, but we are confident that with the right leadership her true nature will shine through.

Daisy’s foster describes her as loyal and hilariously vocal when she greets people she trusts. Generally she is calm and gentle, and likes to be close to her people. Her playful side comes out in bursts, where she loves to dart around the backyard.

Daisy is insecure and will need ongoing support from her forever family. In her amazing foster home, she has done well and taken steps in the right direction. She is currently being muzzle trained, and it is advised this continues in her forever home. She will require more time than your average dog to decompress in a new environment and begin to trust her new family. Once she is comfortable, training can start to build her confidence and socialization. She is truly a people pleaser, and very sensitive, so only positive reinforcement based training will be permissible for her success.

Daisy's new family will have large dog experience and live in a low traffic area like the suburbs. Her fosters need to remain at least 25 meters from other dogs for Daisy's safety, and the safety of other dogs. Due to this, Daisy will not be suitable for condo or apartment living.

Daisy is medium energy and would do best in a home that can provide her with smaller walks throughout the day, as well as time in the backyard to use the washroom. Daisy is reactive on leash, so she will require a strong and calm leader. When she sees other dogs, she pulls and barks and therefore will require an adopter who is committed to redirecting her attention with treats or a toy when she sees other dogs on walks. New environments and situations are very stressful for Daisy, including walks. She is best walked for shorter periods, in areas where she will have less exposure to triggers. This training will be ongoing, and will require time and patience to help her overcome her insecurities.

True to her breed, she is smart and eager to please. Daisy knows sit, lie down, stay, recall, paw and other fundamental basic commands she is working on in her foster home. Continuing her obedience and trick training will be an important part of confidence building over time.

Daisy is house trained and can be trusted with free reign when left alone. She is not crate trained but chills out in her dog bed or on her favorite part of the couch. When you come home she may bark out of excitement to greet you but settles quickly as long as unbalanced energy is not rewarded. She has not been left alone much, but has shown signs of separation anxiety when she is left alone by whining or crying. Her forever family should be prepared to deal with this as part of her ongoing training.

Daisy’s ideal family will live in a detached, low traffic home as too many visitors in the beginning could potentially hinder her success. Given she is fearful of loud or unexpected movements and noises, she is looking for a home without children or other pets.

If you’re interested in adopting Daisy, please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Daisy's adoption fee is $800 and will be donated towards sessions with a Fetch & Releash approved trainer. To learn more about our adoption fees and the foster-to-adopt process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

animal.description:
Bonnie
2 years old (This is the vet’s guess based on her teeth)
15 lbs
Terrier Mix (This is our best guess, again we don’t know for sure, since she was a street dog)


Other Dogs: Yes - She is good with other dogs.

Cats: Yes - she was in a foster with other cats but will chase the cats if they run, but not hurt them.

Kids: Adult home only - she is shy and timid and is scared by fast movements when trying to pet her. 

Housebroken: No - Bonnie hates the cold weather and we are having a hard time potty training her.

Leash Trained: No - Bonnie needs a home with a fenced backyard. She is also doggy door trained. Apartments and condos are not a good fit for Bonnie.

Crate Trained: Yes

Sheds: No

Barks: No

Car Rides: She is nervous in the car


Bonnie is a beautiful full of life and loving girl. Bonnie is very playful with other dogs. She has lots of energy but also likes to cuddle and be loved on. Bonnie was rescued from the streets of a small village with a pack of 8 dogs. She was very emaciated. It’s was apparent that she had just had a litter of puppies. Although no puppies were ever found. Bonnie has since gained weight and some muscle. 


Bonnie has deformed legs --- Bonnie loves to play with other dogs. Although he can over do it at times. By the end of the day she is tired and worn out. She has shown some signs of discomfort (limping) when she over does it. Bonnie won’t be able to hike or walk miles. She will need short walks and lower activity (she is a great couch snuggle buddy). She would also do well on some joint supplements and some anti inflammatory meds. 


She has old trauma to her legs. Her left leg is worse than her right leg. One is an old fracture that healed wrong the other was from trauma being hit by a car. 


We currently have her on a joint/bone supplement to help stop any bone deterioration or osteoporosis. Our vet in Mexico will send his report and the xrays, that we took on Bonnie's legs.


Could you be her happily ever after?


Bonnie was rescued in Guadalajara, Mexico and fostered in Mexico through our organization “The MexiMutt Project” (You can read more about our organization on Facebook and Instagram). Please keep in mind that our dogs are rescued off the streets or were living outside 24/7 --- so they are NOT always 100% housebroken and will need time to adjust and transition.


Adoption fee is $550 - that covers all of the vaccines (DHLPP, Rabies and Bordetella), current on flea/tick treatment, fecal testing, deworming, sterilization (spay/neuter), Heartworm-Lyme-Ehrlichia-Anaplasma Blood Test, dental cleaning (if needed), Distemper and Parvo blood test to make sure the dog is disease-free, Health Certificate, Microchip with registration, grooming before transport and the flight transport from Guadalajara, Mexico to Portland, Oregon. We will also send the dog home with a brand new collar, ID tag, leash and a small bag of the kibble.


Fill out an online adoption application here: www.BAPBR.org


*Please know that we are a 100% volunteer ran organization, with no paid employees and we work full time jobs and have our own families to care for as well. Due to the large number of applications we receive - we are not able to reply to everyone individually. If we think you are the right match for our dog, we will reach out to you and set up a meet and greet. Thank you in advance for understanding.

*Snoopy is a sweet, shy, boy around 21 pounds.  He is on medication for his kidney function.  *Sophie is around 19 pounds.

I know. You look at us and all you see are two scared pups. I can't blame you. Lately, life has been pretty scary. You see, our owner surrendered us, and though we don't understand why, we're trying to start over. My name is Sophie and this is Snoopy, he is my best friend. I'll let you in on a little secret: Snoopy really needs me to look out for him. He's not very brave so I have to be brave for both of us, but that's what big sisters do. Okay, another little secret: Snoopy is not really my brother, but he's 11 and I'm about 7 so I think it works anyway because we been together all of our lives. Would it work for you? Would you come see us? We would love to meet you!

If you would like to meet one of our Homeless Pets at the Town and Country Veterinary Clinic it is best to fill out an application first and schedule an appt. (as we are based out of a busy Veterinary Office)

Marietta, GA 30062

animal.description:
Name: Mille
Breed: Puggle (Pug/Beagle)
Sex: Female
Age: 12 yr old
Color: fawn
Weight: 21 pounds
Characteristic: Adorable floof who lives for snackies! 

Name:  Charlie
Breed: Puggle (Pug/Beagle)
Sex: Male
Age: 12 yr old
Color: apricot 
Weight: 24 pounds
Characteristic: Sweet snuggler who loves to be close!

Millie and Charlie must be adopted together, they are currently fostered in the Tampa area. 


Hello puggle friends and Happy New Year! We are Millie & Charlie, an adorable puggle pair, looking for a family to help us ring in 2021.

We have been together our entire lives and need to stay together forever. When you see how sweet we are you will be happy to have 2 times the puggle love! 

We are both 12 yrs old. Millie is a fawn female and weighs 21 pounds. Charlie is an apricot-colored male and weighs 24 lbs. They are both good with kids and dogs (we haven't seen them around cats, so we don't know about that). The love a good routine and are potty trained (they have even learned to use a doggie door). 

Millie is an adorable little floof! She is fairly independent. You will never have to watch the clock when she is around...she knows exactly when it is mealtime and will make sure to remind you!  In true puggle fashion she definitely thinks with her stomach. 

She absolutely loves having her ears rubbed. 

She is up to date on her vaccines, heartworm negative, and has had a dental.

Charlie is a snuggler! If you are looking for a snuggle bug to curl up with you and a good book, he is your guy! If you sit down Charlie will figure out a way to sit next to you...and he is a leaner too. If there isn't room beside you, he will ask you to make room on your lap! You absolutely can't resist this sweet boy. 

He is up to date on his vaccines and heartworm negative. He is beginning to show signs of some arthritis, but his mobility is excellent. 

If you think Millie & Charlie might be a great fit for your family, please complete an adoption application today at https://pugrescueofflorida.org/adopt

If you love me but can't adopt me please consider making a donation to rescue to help pay medical bills for not just me but my fellow foster brothers and sisters.

My Rescue friends are working very hard to find me and the other foster pugs new homes, so please be sure to submit an application before contacting them.

More information and  applications are available at WWW.PUGRESCUEOFFLORIDA.ORG
animal.name: Millie & Charlie

animal.description:
Barney is a male yellow Labrador mix who came to our rescue as a stray. His established date if birth is July 2020.
Since Barney is a stray,  we don't have any back round information about him. That's why we are a foster home based rescue, so we can gather the personality information and make sure Barney is matched up with the best home. 
The foster family has other dogs and cats in the home but no children. Barney has lots of energy and will need an active family to keep him busy and channel his energy to positive learning. 
All medical work is completed prior to adoption including neutering shots worming flea treatment rabies shot micro chip and vet exam. 
Adoption fee is $150 + tax with an approved application. 
Prairie Paws Rescue does not adopt on a first come basis but who will provide the best home suited to the pets needs

animal.description:
Beatrice the Beabull 
STATE: Western NY 
AGE: 7 years
DOB: unsure
WEIGHT: 72 lbs
SEX: Female
NEUT/UTD: YES/YES
COAT COLOR: Brindle/white
DOCKED TAIL: YES
CROPPED EARS: NO
CHILDREN under 4: NO (NO HISTORY)
CHILDREN OVER 4: YES
SEPARATION ANXIETY: NO
OTHER DOGS: YES
CATS: No (no History)
CRATE TRAINED: YES
HOUSE TRAINED: yes
OBEDIENCE TRAINED: NO
LEASH TRAINED: NO
MICROCHIPPED:  YES
ADOPTION FEE: $475

1/16/21-Beatrice is doing great! She’s such an easy dog to have around. She is getting more comfortable each day and even wiggles her nub now. I’ve yet to hear her bark, she’s just a quiet little gal. Her temperament has been amazing, especially considering she was in a mill for 7 long years. 
Beatrice gets along with both of my dogs and other foster extremely well. She tries to play with the other dogs but we are still careful because of her stitches. Once they come out next week she will be free to play away. She is also SO good about wearing her cone overnight or when we can’t watch her. She actually leans towards me so I can easily put it on! I’ve never had a dog so accepting of wearing a cone. Beatrice isn’t much for toys yet but hopefully will figure that out. She does like to explore the yard and check things out. She is also completely housebroke, she had 1 accident within her first few minutes here and that is it. Again, I’m amazed after 7 years in a cage she’s SO good. She does have her moments when she gets scared and goes to her safe place (crate) but those times are getting fewer and fewer. Beatrice would really dog great in most homes. She is so happy with any bit of love and attention she gets and is a joy to have around. 

1/9/21 Beatrice the Beabull has arrived yesterday after a long few days. Beatrice was a release from a puppy mill. After spending several days at our vet clinic where she was brought up to date and had a lump/cyst removed from her face she then jumped on a transport to WNY just in time for the Buffalo Bills playoff game! Beatrice is 7 years old and must have been spay due to complications with her last litter. Since she can’t produce puppies anymore she got her lucky break and came to rescue. Beatrice is a super sweet girl. She’s a bit shy but not as bad as most mill dogs. I have no doubts she will come around quickly. She really likes exploring the yard which is great since she needs to shed some weight. Unfortunately living in a cage with no exercise has caused her to be overweight. I got her some weight management food today so hopefully she will feel full while shedding some pounds. I think now that she has her freedom the weight will come off slowly and surely. Beatrice will have her sutures removed in about 10 days then will be ready for her own special family! More updates coming soon.

animal.description:
Sweet Chloe was one of two Mals dumped a few weeks ago at the Redlands Rock Pit area, a famous 'dog dumping ground.' She and her pal Avery (also available for adoption through MAD Rescue) were being fed by local volunteers who alerted our rescue. These sweet girls are terrified, but couldn't be any sweeter if they tried.

They were found covered in ticks and fleas, infested with hookworms, and in desperate need of some TLC. MAD Rescue took them immediately to the vet, where they were de-wormed, bathed, groomed, and vaccinated. Chloe is currently settling into her foster home where we'll learn more about her personality. We'll update her profile as we know more. Chloe and her gal pal Avery are avalible to adopt indivually or as a pair. Please note on your application.

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

From her Mom: Jayne is about 10 years old. She is a darling (but very shy) fawn and white pittie girl. She lived on the streets her whole life until we took her in. She takes a while to warm up to people but is never aggressive even when she is around new people- just shy. She is about 50 pounds. You can tell she is a darling girl who wants to trust... she just needs reassurance. She does best with positive reinforcement and would excel in a home where she is with another shy or submissive playmate similar in size and of the opposite sex. She does like to shred her blankets in her crate so setting her up with a thicker rubber mat to sleep on is ideal for her. She loves treats and she will find them if you aren't the best at hiding them or you forget them somewhere where she can reach them. Jayne was rescued with her puppies back in 2013.

Meet Atlas!
-7 years old
- GSD

Atlas is young at heart, always has a smile on his face, and keeps up easily with dogs half his age! He came into the rescue needing FHO surgery so he will be going the process very soon followed by up to 6 weeks of rehabilitation before he begins his heartworm treatment. Nicknamed the "King of the toys" he likes to collect all the toys in the house and make his own little pile to lay in. Loves food and great on the leash. Crate & house trained, including dog door. We have not tested with cats or kids yet, but we can if an approved adopter requests it after his surgery.

**Atlas is heartworm positive and will be starting the treatment process shortly after his upcoming FHO surgery. We allow pre-adoption of our heartworm positive dogs while they complete their treatment & crate rest at their foster home 30 days after the heartworm injections**

Interested in adding Atlas to your family? Start the process by filling out an application through the 'More About Us' link to the right or asking us a question about Atlas!

animal.description:
Hi, I am Lulu! I was deemed Agile Lulu because you will not see me miss out on any physical challenge just because I'm a tripod. I can run faster and I have better balance than my four legged friends at my foster home! 
link to video: https://youtu.be/FEul6a-Yhzc

I am a 2 year old, 64 pound Belgian Malinois Shepherd girl in search for my forever home. I am also a tripod - I lost a rear leg prior to coming into rescue, but that doesn't slow me down one bit. In fact, I am still the fastest and most agile dog in my foster home! This is no lie. When I fly past you at the park, you'll see!
I walk on leash, am very well crate- and house-trained, love to go for car rides (I can easily jump into the highest of vehicles) and I am very social with other dogs! I am an easy part of the pack. I play well with other dogs with my toys, but I always seem to get my favorite toy first and hang on to it all day. I am very food and treat motivated, so you can use these to help train me for specific things! But, since I am so food motivated, it is better to give me a quiet space to eat my food, such as in my crate, so I dont get scared that I am going to lose my meal to others. I get too excited around cats or pigs, so I am best in a home only with other large playful dogs I have been with many large dogs in my foster home and get along very well with all of them! I even back down if they get too pushy with me. My favorite thing in the world is to play fetch. In fact, if you watch my adoption video, you will see just how agile and fast I am and how much I love fetch. I love to carry my Kong toy with me everywhere - even to the vet clinic! I pretty much live to play. If you are considering me, you should research my breed a bit - we are high-energy dogs that are very motivated to play, and we need to play every day. So, if you are an active person who wants to take me on runs and hikes, and play fetch with me daily, we could be the perfect match! I do need exercise and I would love to have a yard. Even though I love to run and play, if you sit down on the grass, I am going to come sit next to you and give you a kiss and cuddle to you a bit before I run off for more fun. Please do watch my adoption video and contact my adoption coordinator if you think we might be right for each other! I look forward to a lifetime of fun and adventure with you!
This sweet, sassy, one of a kind tripod Belgian Malinois is already spayed, up to date on vaccines, deworming and ready for a new home. Missing one leg does not slow her down and anyone would be so lucky to bring her home. 
The reason we are looking for a home with no small children or small animals is because LuLu has high drive, and when she goes for her toys it can sometimes be rough in a moment of excitement. We do not want anyone or anything to be hurt by accident while she is diving excitedly for her Kong. She can get overly excited and can be pushy and need direction. Not an abnormal behavior for many breeds, just needs direction. She needs a dog savvy adopter who will embrace her activity level and bring her along for adventures!

please email alayna@threelittlepittiesrescue.org with any questions!

Lulu is fully vetted and in excellent condition according to the veterinarian!

animal.description:
Dorota is a sweet 2 1/2 month old puppy that will arrive to us on January 30th from our Louisiana shelter partner.  

She has been in a foster home in Louisiana since she was just a few days old. Foster reports she is cuddly and very smart, gets along well with other dogs and kids


Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
The puppies in Amber's litter were born on 12/24/2020 when Amber was safely at Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue after being on the euthanasia list at a Tulsa shelter. These puppies can't be adopted until they are 8 weeks old, which will be 2/18/2021. We will add more information as each puppy's personality develops. 

Before applying to adopt a Pit Bull or Pit Bull mix, you need to be familiar with your local breed-specific legislation regarding Pit Bulls. Applicants must live within 50 miles of the Omaha/Council Bluffs area.

Since this puppy may be too young to be altered at the time of adoption, the adopters will be provided with a voucher to have the puppy altered and microchipped by the time he is 6 months of age. This must be done at Nebraska Humane Society. If you prefer to take the puppy to your own vet, we will pay a PORTION of the cost ($69) to your vet of choice.

The suggested adoption donation for this puppy is $450. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

If you are interested in meeting a dog or cat, we require an adoption application. If the animal has "HAS APPLICATION" listed, they are still available to receive additional applications but also may be in the process of being adopted soon. Apply for a DOG: http://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/adoptable-dogs.html

Interested in saving more lives? Foster a dog today! Learn more, see our list of dogs needing foster, and apply, https://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/foster-a-city-dog.html

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster-based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first-served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

animal.description: Gizmo is a  sweet 6 year old female Chi/ JackRussel Mix. If you are looking for a total lap dog Gizzy is your girl! animal.description: Please meet Allie.  This beautiful, sweet, house-broken girl is just over four years old.  Her dark grey and white markings are quite striking!   Allie loves people and has never meet a stranger.  She has not been around young children, and due to her size and strong desire to be a lap dog, she would do best in a home with older kids.  Allie enjoys car rides and loads up like a champ.  She loves to play fetch, but instead of bring her toys back to you, she will proudly prance around while carrying them in her mouth.  In true lab fashion, Allie will even take her favorite ball to bed with her at night.  Allie is crate trained  and is well behaved and quiet in the house.  She has never been destructive while home alone or while waiting in the vehicle.  Allie seems to enjoy the company cats and has been around cows and horses without issue.  Allie has gotten along with medium/large male dogs in the past, but she can be picky about her female friends.  Allie would do best in a home with an experienced dog owner or as an only dog.  What this 66-pound lap dog wants most is to have her very own human to love!

animal.description:
Hi. My name is Daisy and I am a 2 year old Australian Shepherd mix.  I am an owner surrender and don’t quite understand what is going on. 

I love to play outside in the snow. I know how to sit. I love people. I have lots of love to give. I seem to be house-trained. I am very protective. I don’t let anything in my yard. I would do best as an only pet . I do not get along with other dogs. I live with 2 cats but we are not friends. I bark at them, but not excessively. When I hear new noises, I will let you know. I have a kennel, but don’t use it when my humans are gone.  I don’t enjoy car rides. I drool a lot.  

I weigh 65 pounds, but it is all tail.  

Do I sound like a good fit for you? If so, send a text and set up a meet. 

Adoption Fee: $350 (no checks) 

Dog Coordinator:  Jaime 651-324-1105 or Jaime3369@gmail.com

Due to the recommendations about the coronavirus, we are not able to have group adoption events at PetSmart.  We are, however, allowed to do individual adoptions so if you are interested in this pup/dog, please contact the foster listed above to set up a meeting.  We look forward to continuing to save dogs with you and will resume group adoptions as soon as we can.  Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home.  An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home.  Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home & truly become comfortable.  There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption; discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, & 3 months.  We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.   

Last Hope, Inc. is an all volunteer, foster based, no kill rescue! You can see almost all of our dogs on Saturdays from 11am - 3pm at Lakeville PetSmart (located by Hy-Vee just off 160th & Pilot Knob) & Burnsville Petsmart (located just off Hwy 35E & County Rd 42 by Chianti Grill).

Policies: You do not have to have a fence to adopt a dog from us, but some dogs will require a fence or acres to play, or an active family who will make sure the dog gets the exercise it needs to be happy.  Some dogs do not have the temperament that will do well with young children.   

The Adoption Fee is not enough to cover the vet bills. Sales tax of almost 7.25% is also included in the adoption fee that you see. Please consider donating to Last Hope to help us save these animals!

CAN YOU FOSTER? By taking a dog or puppies temporarily into your home and then coming to our adoption days to help find them homes, we can save more! If you’re interested, please email our dog coordinator: jaime3369@gmail.com and give us your contact information and what you would like to foster and someone will get back to you! You can also apply to be a foster home on our webpage! In the upper left hand corner there’s a drop down tab with the link for canine foster home. Just fill it out online & submit! We will get back to you as quick as we can.

animal.description:
Mr. Fritz needs an adopter or a long term foster to love him through his golden years! His former owner, Mr. E has loved Fritz all of his life, but sadly, he has recently had to move into an Alzheimer's facility and Fritz is unable to go with him.

One of our dearest supporters heard about their situation and stepped in to temporarily care for Fritz while we find him a longer term foster or adopter.

Fritz is partly blind, but not totally. He is a little shy but extremely food motivated.

A home with older, calmer dogs where he can relax peacefully in their company or where he can be the only pet would be ideal. He is a senior pooch after all and deserves a relaxing retirement!

?

If you have space in your heart and home for Fritz, please reach out to us asap and we would be more than happy to answer any questions you have! stephanie@wagshopeandhealing.org

Please visit www.handsheartspaws.org for an adoption application

All of our dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, fecal tested, heartworm tested, and they are all on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.

The adoption process is an application, a vet reference, a home visit, and a lifetime contract. The requested adoption donation for this dog is $275___.

We do not REQUIRE a fenced in yard (some dogs DO REQUIRE a fence.  Decide what is best for each dog), we do REQUIRE a means of safe outside containment.  We do NOT adopt to homes that use invisible fencing.  Invisible fencing is NOT a safe means of outside containment.

We are willing to adopt out-of-state, contingent on our ability to complete a home visit, but you must travel to Omaha to complete the adoption. We do not transport or ship our dogs.

animal.description:
Taffy is as sweet as her name! She is about 4 years old and weighs 37 pounds, She was living in a car, along with a cat,  for many years because her owners were homeless. They could no longer care for her and surrendered her to us. Taffy is such a happy, friendly and sweet girl. Her tail is always wagging and she never met a stranger she didn't like!

The reason Taffy is listed as special needs is because she was diagnosed with a condition called megaesophagus. This is characterized by a lack of motility in her esophagus meaning the food does not move into the stomach, but rather sits in the esophagus and causes regurgitation. In addition to medication a solution is to have Taffy eat several small meals and to remain upright for 20 minutes after feeding. There is a chair made especially for this called a Bailey Chair. This allows gravity to assist in moving the food into her stomach. Many dogs adjust well to this condition and can lead happy normal lives. 

If you are interested in meeting Taffy please complete the adoption application at www.greatpets.org. If you have any questions please email us at info@greatpets.org.

animal.description:
They say that eyes are the window to the soul, and I have some of the most beautiful eyes that you'll ever see! My eyes tell a story, that you may or may not want to hear. 

I don't remember how or why I ended up in the shelter on the euthanasia list, but boy was it scary! A foster said yes to me, probably because of my amazing eyes, and she took me home and is giving me all of the loves! 

Don't be afraid of me because I look kinda funny. My previous owners didn't give me any flea medicine, and it turns out that I am pretty darn allergic to the little buggers and it made me lose all of my fur! I think it's growing in quite nicely though now that I have good food and good vet care!

I am friendly with other dogs and very sweet with people. I am a fun, super loving girl who really wants a home that loves me like I love them. If you think I'm the girl for you, just fill out an application to meet me at www.pawsitivetailskc.org. My adoption fee is $150 and I'm up to date on age appropriate vaccines, dewormed, current on preventatives, spayed and microchipped.
