animal.description: As her name suggests, Oreo is a black-and-white girl with an adorable face and very sweet disposition. In her former home, Oreo was a bit of a couch potato, catching z's (that means naps) on the couch, under the bed and wherever her heart desired. She doesn't have as many options in terms of where to sleep here at PACC, so we know she'd love to get back into a home and find some new spots to snooze. In play group, Oreo was a bit nervous but came into the yard with a waggy tail and greeted other dogs appropriately. Her interactions were a bit stiff at first, but she eventually warmed up and engaged in some gentle and dainty play with the other dogs. Oreos is a friendly girl who also likes to cuddle up with staffers and volunteers, soliciting treats and affection. Oreo would do best in a home free from kids, or with kids who are old enough to understand that dogs can need space sometimes. She would also thrive under a dog savvy owner who understands herding breeds and their behavior. If Oreo sounds like the girl for you, make an appointment to meet this big lovebug today.

animal.description: In Greek mythology, Athena was the goddess of wisdom. Well, this Athena is only 2 years old, but we're told she's wise beyond her years. Athena came to PACC after her owner was no longer able to afford her medication. Even though she's a young girl, she's got some a bad hip and has been on medication to help with the pain. She's in need of an operation to repair it and would love to spend her recovery inside of a home instead of at the shelter. In her former home, Athena lived with another dog and a 5 year old child and did well (we're told she loves kids, but isn't as fond of cats.) She's housetrained and was a bit of a couch potato, due to her hip. In play group, Athena was a bit nervous at first, but was tolerant of other dogs and engaged in a little bit of gentle and dainty play. Staffers say she's people-oriented and preferred to stay by her handler. She's a shy girl, but very sweet and friendly with humans and dogs alike. Athena is easy to leash up and walks well, not reacting to other dogs in the kennel or along the way. Athena is a total doll and will make someone a very lucky owner. If Athena sounds like the dog for you, make an appointment to meet her today.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Sweet Amara was born on or around 12/20/2017 and was dumped on the streets of Mobile Alabama with her babies. All of her babies got rescued safely and Amara had to be trapped. AGBR had a pre-arranged foster but unfortunately that fell through. Amara is looking for a forever home that will understand she can be a little shy at first but she warms up quickly and absolutely loves her humans. She is smaller girl weighing only about 20 pounds and is as sweet as she can be. Amara would make the perfect pet for a calm household so she would probably do best with older children. If you are interested in adding Amara to your family, submit your application today.

Amazing Grace Bully Rescue is a foster based rescue in the Pensacola, Florida area. We do not have a physical building. If you would like to meet any of our pups, the first step is to fill out our online application so we can contact you.

Our adoption fee for Amara is $200 and includes her spay, current shots, rabies vaccine, and a registered microchip.

If you would like to adopt this Amazing dog, please fill out our online adoption application at www.amazinggracebullyrescue.org

If you have any questions, please text your question to
723-2037
. You may also send a message to our Amazing Grace Bully Rescue Page on Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, or send an email directly to amazinggracebullyrescue@gmail.com

Disclaimer: We are located in the Pensacola, Florida area and will consider local applicants first, especially with puppies since we use a vet in the local area.

animal.description:
After the Mona Lisa, Da Vinci would surely have painted Donatella as she sounds like a super model, has the looks and class of one and will surely be the talk of the town as well. Donatella is a gorgeous young Walker Hound who has stunning markings in the standard tri color pattern inherent to her breed. She is about a year old and is small for a hound, weighing only about 35 lbs though she wouldn't turn down an extra treat or two if offered to become a bit curvier. Donatella is a confident gal around other dogs but clearly has not had a lot of positive interactions with humans so is a bit shy, though warming up more and more every day. This gal would love a home with another dog, or 5, doesn't matter to her as she is well versed in dog language and camaraderie. She would likely prefer a home with somewhat older children who are less startling with the noises they make and good snuggling buddies all the while. She would love a fenced in yrad to be a hound, sniffing here and sniffing there and will soon settle inot a wonderful routine with your family that gives her confidence and security, things she has likely never had before. Donatella is a true beauty with a gentle soul and is waiting to become the star painting in your family.

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

An adult tri-colored hound weighing 40 lbs or so, Gunner is as handsome and easy-going as they come.

He enjoys long naps and casual strolls around the block.

You'll fall in love with his sweet hound face and floppy ears. He always gets excited about mealtime! Gunner is content to sit by your side or take a nap with you and is a pro at making a bed out of anything, but he will get into his crate with no issue and sleep through the night. Gunner knows to go potty outside and will go to the door to let you know it's time to go out. He gets along great with other dogs but would be perfectly happy living solo as well, or with a feline companion. He rides well in the car and will be a happy passenger wherever you go. animal.description:
www.huskyrescueteam.org

If you have additional questions please email info@huskyrescueteam.org
Hockey is our first rescue of 2021!

Hockey is a two year old Siberian Husky who we saved from a shelter in NC. Hockey's owner knew he was at the shelter and never came for him. He is heartworm positive so we will be working on bringing him back to health this new year.

He's hooman and dog friendly and has been on his best behavior while waiting for us to save him. Hockey is starting to come out of his shell and open up. He's a pretty mild mannered guy for a young Husky and likes to play with the other dogs in his foster home. He's submissive in nature and really just a big sweetheart.

Hockey is potty trained and communicative when he needs something. He'd like a forever home with a fenced yard and another canine to play with. He's not been small kid tested but would be fine with older children. You do not need breed experience to adopt Hockey but please educate yourself on our website: www.huskyrescueteam.org/education

We will be using the slow kill method to treat Hockey's heartworms and will provide an Adopter all medication until he's negative. So he can be adopted now. His adoption area is NJ to NC.

www.huskyrescueteam.org
~~Husky Education And Rescue Team is a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in our foster homes all up and down the east coast. We do not have a facility in which you can visit. We find this a huge benefit because we learn our dogs and are able to educate our adopters on what it's like to have them live in your home. Part of our process, once pre-approved, is to speak with the foster for the dog you're interested in. If you're still interested in adopting from our rescue the first step is to complete our adoption application online at www.huskyrescueteam.org/apply

If you have additional questions please email info@huskyrescueteam.org

animal.description:
Yukon, called “Yuki”, is a 10-week-old female pup, a Border Collie mix.

Yuki was a surprise.  Here is the background story --
Ali and Uni, two of the three pups from the “Roadside Litter” were rescued on 12/28/20. “Why Roadside?”, you ask. Pups were spotted some weeks ago, crossing the street while following their Mama, here on the Navajo Nation.  It took some detective work but finally we found that Mama and Papa were raising pups just off the road, living in a “hole”. While the goal of this rescue was to rescue the whole family, Mama and Papa started leaving pups alone longer and longer and pups were at risk of getting run over, and when we went to get them all, only two pups were there, Uni and Ali, no Yuki.  Two weeks later, Yuki was found nearby, in the back of a school, near an empty barn.  Given her markings and size, she is undoubtedly a littermate of Ali and Uni.  

Yuki has been in foster care, along with her litter-mates for nearly a week.  At first, Yuki was aggressive and striving to be the alpha in the pack, likely due to fear, since she was on her own for more than 2 weeks.  Luckily, it did not take long for her to learn how to be a pup again and get along.  Her bigger sister, Ali, appears to be the pack’s alpha and Yuki is making progress daily.  She is already spending 100% of her time with her sisters, unsupervised, including overnight, in their kennel. They play and play. (Yuki got the “best bather” award. Some of the pictures posted are of her “after bath”.)

Yuki is fast! She is playful and as a Border Collie type dog, she is smart, active, and is likely to be large, probably 60-70 pounds.  She currently 10 weeks old, 15 pounds feels safe inside and in the backyard. 

Like any pup, Yuki loves to chew on things, is playful, is learning potty-training and is about to start leash-walking this week.  She has already started wanting pets from her foster Mama and is doing good at snuggling, for a beginner. It helps that her litter-mates show her how!

UPDATE:
Vet appointment coming up. Yuki took to leash walking like a champ.  She is still a pup, very "mouthy" but we are working through this stage.

Foster Mama Tiasha requests that you fill out the online application at blackhathumanesociety.org AND email her at tveselames@gmail.com and tell a bit about you, what you are looking for in a dog, your daily activity level, experience with smart/active/larger breeds,… 

At Blackhat, we strive to match the needs of the dog with the needs of the adopter.

animal.description:
Fiona is in a foster home in Kent WA

***Please DO NOT send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available. If a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder- we are still accepting applications for them***

Hi there! Let's get the medical notes out of the way first and see if you still think Fiona would be a good fit :)

Fiona was in a foster-to-adopt home recently & they took her to see a vet and we discovered that she has a heart murmur. We do not know the severity at this time, but will be getting xrays to determine if she will require medication or not. Many dogs live long, healthy lives with heart murmurs and you would never know! We will pay for the xrays and are working on getting her into a vet at this time for a further work up.

Fiona, 1 years old, Female pitbull. Fiona is the sweetest puppy you’ll ever meet! She is one of those girls that makes the perfect best friend. She is a little shy at first and does take a little while to warm up, but once she does, she'll be your best friend! This means that she will require someone who will be PATIENT with her and allow her the time she needs to decompress. She loves car rides and is very obedient. You only have to show her once and she’s got it.   She is definitely a people person with a very loyal temperament. She would rather be with you than out playing with the others. She has a very calm, easygoing energy level. If you sit down she wants to lay at your feet (or sit in your lap!). She is house trained and has no problem being put in her kennel. Fiona is cutest when she’s burying herself in her blankets. She is very calm and quiet. It’s very easy to forget she’s there. She is dog friendly, but again, she requires SLOW introductions when meeting any new doggie friends. After being in her foster home for only a week, she showed some signs of being possessive over toys with other dogs, but was easily corrected and allowed for the toy to be taken away from her by her person. She has been cat tolerant but likes to chase them. Decompression is KEY for sweet Fiona. 

Due to Fiona's puppy energy we recommend a home with no kids under the age of 12. 

***Listed BREED and AGE - We are taking our best guess on age, breed and size when fully grown. We rarely know a dog's exact age nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time.

The first step in our process is filling out an application. We will review your application as soon as we are able- there are two of us and we do the best that we can. We review applications on a first come first serve basis and look for the best fit/match for dog and applicant.

https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Name: Figgy
Age: 2 or 3 years old
Gender: Female
Location: Houston, TX
Adoption Fee: $350

Figgy is a beautiful 2 or 3 year old female Shih Tzu mix. Prior to coming to us, she had a very difficult. life. She lived on the streets of Houston for more than a year (judging by how badly she was matted). She was extremely nervous when she came to her foster home. The other dogs would try to play with her but Figgy thought they were attacking her and she ran. She did not trust dogs or humans. 

It didn't take long for Figgy to adjust to family life. Now she enjoys it immensely! She loves to run and play with her foster siblings. She's still trying to figure out how to interact with humans. She sometimes bites playfully. She rubs herself all over her human, marking them maybe? She has some odd quirks but they make her unique!

Figgy has some mineral deposits on her spine. She has been treated with medication and crate rest. As of today, Figgy is doing great! She runs and jumps around pain free. Our vet has cautioned us that Figgy could possibly have future back issues and could require surgery. There's no way to tell if that will happen or when. If you are interested in Figgy, please be prepared for the expense of treating back issues up to and including surgery by a specialist.

**We have very limited transport options. If you are chosen to adopt Figgy, please be prepared to travel to Houston, TX to pick her up. If we can assist with transport, we will let you know.

For information on our adoption process including adoption fees, please read our Adoption Information page at http://chinesecrestedrescue.org/adoption-info/

If you're interested in Figgy, email info@chinesecrestedrescue.org or complete an application online, http://chinesecrestedrescue.org/application-adopt-volunteer/

Meet Sam! Sam is Terrier mix, about a year old, and weighs 12 pounds. He is looking for a loving and patient home. Sam truly enjoys daily walks and is great on the leash. He does get a little excited when he sees other dogs, but totally manageable with a "keep on moving along". Sam is always up for a good game of fetch and soccer with his toys. He also loves napping in his crate and frolicking outdoors in the sunshine. Sam loves to cuddle and is a straight up sucker for belly rubs. There are also a few things that are important to know about Sam. We don't know if Sam had a bad experience and/or if it's just in his nature to be a bit anxious. Here's the deal with Sam. It takes a minute to get to know him and build trust. He isn't the dog you will meet and greet with and fall head over heels in love with. Sam needs; kindness, love, patience, space, time and most of all, respect of his need for all of these things in order to give him the time to learn and love you...truly let you in to see and experience the sunshine in his heart. He needs that person or people that WANT to invest in a dog that takes a little extra effort and patience. Sam is anxious around new things, especially loud and hearty energy. We don't recommend children in the home because of this, so if you are planning on having human babies down the road, Sam isn't the one. Sam likes to chill in his crate for a daily nap...and if there are new people coming over, he doesn't mind being in his safe place until he gets comfy and used to new people. He will probably always need to be woken up by sound vs. touch, as he has reacted by nipping when startled awake. Sam also doesn't like to be cornered, just something we have learned about and continue to respect. Sam is a very sweet and loving boy, once he is comfortable and trusts you. He is on the shy side, so meeting new people and friends isn't vibe. He's cool with his small circle of peeps. Sam truly enjoys playing outside, so a home with a yard would be ideal for him. We think Sam would enjoy being the only animal in the home, so that is a requirement. We know Sam isn't perfect, but he will be someone's perfect fit. If you have a soft spot for pooches that need and deserve a little extra effort, and know that with time and patience, the reward will far outweigh the effort...he could be your special someone.

If you are interested in adopting, please visit the I.C.A.R.E. Dog Rescue website and complete an adoption application: www.icaredogrescue.org/ready-to-adopt

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter shots up to date micro-chip fecal and vet check

Click here to watch a video of Sam.

animal.description:
READ FULL BIO + INFO before applying at heartsforpawsrescue.com/adoption-application

Meet Honey — a 2-3 year old medium size breed mutt who came to us all the way from Iran. We do not know much about where she came from or her backstory, however Honey did live in a foster home in Iran prior to arrival (foster home had kids and dogs). 

Honey is gentle, shy, nervous, timid and sweet — she has zero aggression but will need a patient home committed to continued confidence and trust building + desensitization and positive exposure.

She may do best with another calm dog friend and a big yard. She is learning to walk well on leash but can still get nervous about somethings and halt/pancake to the ground. She is still learning that stairs are not scary and her foster home is the second floor apartment so she has to be carried, but we are hoping she can master the stairs in no time.

Moderate energy — she is still decompressing and so we have not seen her full personality yet. She has wonderful potential with the right home.

May do well in a home w/ cats given slow intros. Recommend home teens plus.

$300 adoption donation helps cover costs of travel and vetting — spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, heartworm/fecal tested and up to date on monthly preventatives.

We are unsure her true breeds  — she is about 45 lbs. Age guess best 2-3 years.

*******************************************************************************************

Adoption Process:

Step 1. Complete online adoption application including pictures of home / yard

Step 2. If it sounds like a good fit for all we will respond in 1-5 days to schedule a follow up call with an adoption counselor. Due to a high amount of interest for puppies, we may not be able to respond to all applicants but will try our best!

Step 3. If it sounds like a match, we will promptly set up a meet and greet at the foster home’s backyard or outdoor public setting practicing social distancing policies. Please review info on meet and greets at heartsforpawsrescue.com/meet-greet-info

More info & FAQS can be found at:

heartsforpawsrescue.com/adoption-info

We can keep adoption applications on file for up to 6 months that can be used for other HFP adoptable dogs.

Name: Shakespeare & Ellie
Age: 9 & 6 years old
Gender: Male/Female
Location: Killeen, TX
Adoption Fee: $600

Shakespeare and Ellie are a bonded pair and need to find a home where they can remain together. Shakespeare is a nine year old hairless male and Ellie’s dad. Ellie is a six year old powder puff female and has been with him her entire life.

They are spayed and neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, heartworm negative and on preventative. They both behave well in their kennels although they have free run of the house except for longer periods. They are housebroken if let out regularly or kenneled for longer periods. Shakespeare has also made use of a belly band on occasion just to be safe. This is a good idea during cold and wet weather.

They love their separate beds to lounge in and love toys! They share toys and do not fight over them although they have their favorites.

Both are very nervous and timid when meeting new people. I found that slices of hot dog are the key to becoming their new best friend! 

**We have very limited transport options. If you are chosen to adopt this bonded pair, please be prepared to travel to Killeen, TX to pick them up. If we can assist in transport, we will let you know.

For information on our adoption process including adoption fees, please read our Adoption Information page at http://chinesecrestedrescue.org/adoption-info/

If you're interested in Shakespeare and Ellie, email info@chinesecrestedrescue.org or complete an application online, http://chinesecrestedrescue.org/application-adopt-volunteer/

animal.description:
Say hello to Frankie! Frankie is a young pittie-mix who is doing extremely well in his foster home. He's a giant wiggle butt, and loves to give kisses and really wants to be a lap dog! He prefers to be right near his human! Because he is so enthusiastically friendly, we recommend no small children, as he could knock them over. Likewise, he's good with other dogs, but is a very energetic player! He has met a few cats respectfully but did want to play with them, and did back off when the cat said no. So, there is potential for him to live with cats.

Frankie is fully housetrained and crate trained (sleeps in crate with no issues), and he's a quiet dog who only barks when someone is at the door or he hears the neighbors dog barking. He's not destructive, but loves to tear up a good squeaky toy :)  He isn't a beggar, and isn't food motivated, really only praise motivated, which has made it easy for his foster mom to train him to sit, stay, come, etc. 

Through some trial and error, Frankie's foster mom has determined the best way to get this guy to comfortably walk on a leash without going after his leash, is to have him in a rear latching harness with a "gentle leader" which still allows him to drink and bark, but keeps him from biting his leash.

Interested? Fill out an application at www.maggiesmissionrescue.org

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting Bronx, please fill out an adoption application at www.evenchance.org/adopt

WE ARE LOOKING TO PLACE BRONX AS AN ONLY DOG.

1.	What is your name?

My name is Bronx.

2.	How old are you?
	
I am about five months old (birthday August, 2020).

3.	What do you look like?

I am a beautiful fawn color with a dark mask muzzle (very dreamy if I do say so myself).

4.	What do you like to eat?

I like the puppy kibble and raw food that momma gives me.  Although truth be known, I prefer the raw (don’t judge).  Sometimes there is gravy on it too or goat’s milk, so good.  

5.	What kind of personality do you have?

I’m an affectionate guy that loves to learn, play and explore.  Whenever I see my foster family, I can’t help but wiggle all over.  However, sometimes being around other dogs tends to bring out not so good qualities, so prefer not to share my people.  

6.	Describe your perfect day

My perfect day is hanging out with my foster mom and learning all the important things I need to know to be a good big dog.  Learning is literally my favorite thing to do (next to eating, can’t forget that).  Then a good cuddle and a relaxing nap.   

7.	What is your favorite toy?

My favorite toys are my stuffed rhino and blue chuck it ball.  I also love a good marrow bone, those things are tasty.  I don’t like to share, momma says you think I grew up as an only child, but no, I just don’t like to share.  Sorry not sorry.

8.	Do you know any tricks?
	
I don’t know any tricks per se, but I’m learning lots of good things each day.  

9.	What scares you?

I’m not really afraid of many things.  I’m very curious and like to explore, however those big cars still make me pretty nervous and sometimes sick (momma says I’m doing good though and I will get over this hurdle).

10.	Do you like cats?

I’m not sure, never met one.

11.	Do you have any doggie best friends?
	
I currently live with three older females but my time with them is very managed.  As I said earlier, I prefer not to share with other dogs.  

12.	If you could be anywhere in the world, where would it be?

Next to momma learning.

13.	How is your health?

According to my veterinarian, I am a healthy, growing puppy.  

14.	How long have you lived in your foster home?

I’ve been with a member of Even Chance since I was a tiny fella.   

15.	Who do you live with in your foster home and who is your closest companion? 
	
I share a beautiful home with my foster parents and foster siblings. I have two high school aged people siblings that I adore and can’t wait to see every single day (seeing them makes my whole body wiggle with joy).  I also have three dog siblings.  All of my foster family is great, but I’m probably closest to my foster mom.  

16.	Where do you hang out when you are home alone?

I always hang out in my crate when there aren’t any people home.  

17.	Where do you sleep?
	
I always sleep in my crate at night, but while my family is home, I will lay on my dog bed in the family room or snuggle on the couch.  

18.	What do you love about your foster family?

I love that my foster family is so dedicated to meeting all my needs. I am grateful that Even Chance rescued me! 

19.	What was life like before you were rescued by Even Chance and brought into the welcoming arms of your foster parents?

I was stuck in a basement with my siblings running amuck and not getting the proper nutrition and other critical things I needed.  My future was bleak and I was headed for a terrible life of dog fighting.

Even Chance does not operate on a first come, first serve basis. In most cases we have already decided the type of home and owner we want for our dogs. These opinions are based on the temperament tests we perform prior to accepting the dog into our program and the behaviors the dogs display as they spend time in our homes. Our agency reserves the right to deny acceptance of any dog to an owner who we feel the lifestyle does not match that of the dog. We are in no way judging you or your lifestyle; we simply want to put our dogs in the best living situation possible. We take very seriously the decision we make when it comes to placing one of our dogs in a forever home. If I sound like the perfect pit bull for your and your family and you are interested in giving me a forever home, do not hesitate! Please fill out an application here and my foster family will contact you to schedule an in-person meet and greet. We look forward to meeting any and all interested applicants.

NEW INTAKE: Idgie - female - approx 3 years old - 18.8 pounds - Maltese/Poodle mix

Reason for intake:
We were tagged on a photo of this gal posted in a lost and found pet group by a nice lady in Mooringsport, La. We followed the post hoping that someone would've been able to capture this little girl but after several days of trying no one was able to get her. We went out on Friday 1/15/21 and unfortunately we had no sighting of her but we went out again on Saturday 1/16/21 and attempted again today and through the help of some neighbors we pinpointed where she was hanging out. As we were talking on the side of the road to several neighbors we spotted her lying at the edge of the woods. We asked the neighbors to go back to their homes so that we could set a trap. We set the trap with some steaming hot fried chicken and drove a distance away and within probably 10 minutes we had her. We named her Idgie after a character in the movie "Fried Green Tomatoes" because the nearby town of Mooringsport reminded us of the town in that movie. Special thanks to all the neighbors who tried to help this little girl. What an amazing group of people. Little Idgy is fed, given a capstar to get rid of the fleas and ticks, started deworming and we were able to get off quite a bit of her matting with the exception of her front paws that were very sensitive. She is rested and warm with a full belly and a nice soft bed. She'll be heading to the vet the week of 1/18/21 to take care of all of her vetting. Welcome little Idgie! Because a lot has happened to her and she is still a flight risk, we are going to make sure we settle her in completely before placing her for adoption.

NOT TAKING APPLICATIONS: We are not taking applications yet. We will post when s(he) is ready for adoption. In the interest of fairness, EARLY application submissions will NOT be considered. Please note we cannot respond to messages/emails, etc., on dogs that are NOT yet available for adoption. Please wait until the dog is available for adoption. We appreciate your cooperation and understanding.

animal.description:
Once blackys owner realized they were allergic to him, he was tied outside on a chain and there he sat for years until his owner finally decided to find him a new home... so we stepped in! He is currently living with 3 other dogs in his foster home, male and female, but can be dog “selective”, so while he’s not dog aggressive, he won’t be the dog you take on dog park trips! He is not a fan of cats, so absolutely no cats. He has great house manners and is fully house and kennel trained! He knows sit, lay down, stay, and is working on rollover. 

Blacky isn’t much of a barker, and really enjoys his daily runs/walks, but also loves his spot next to you on the couch for a good movie. 

He loves to play ball, and has a crazy obsession with his squeaky toys! 

Blacky is FULL of character and will keep you laughing, and great you daily with a full body wag when you get home. 

He is a wonderful boy who is looking for the right home that will allow him to be an active member of the family. Blacky has met kids and due to his size/strength we are asking for a home with older kids.

animal.description:
Zara is a beautiful, energetic, and athletic Blue Heeler/ Australian Cattle. She is about 1 year old and weighs 38 pounds. This lively girl hasn't had much training, but is smart and eager to learn. She gets along with other dogs but has a lot of herding drive and can be nippy.

She needs a canine companion that enjoys rough play and can tolerate herding behavior. Zara loves to play chase and tug of war. With her speed, strength, and stamina, she would be excellent at agility, nose works, barn hunts, and obedience training.

Zara needs a home experienced with herding dogs and a big fenced yard is required. She needs a family that will provide positive training to keep her smart mind engaged and lots of activity and exercise for this high energy youngster.

If you would like to make Zara a member of your family, please submit our on-line application at:

https://www.almosthomehdr.org/apply

animal.description:
UNITY WAS SUPPOSE TO TRANSPORT TO San Francisco BUT DID NOT; SORRY San Franciscans!  SHE AND HER BROTHER ARE AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION IN San Diego AREA 

Unity, born first week of August.

 Applications at karmicrescue.org. 

ESTIMATED ADULT WEIGHT:  50 to 55 pounds

Unity and Peace have great loving, gentle, friendly natures. They are siblings but do not need to be adopted together. They play well with each other and other dogs in foster care. At night they sleep in a crate. As just puppies, they will look to their humans for guidance, routines, and exercise that slowly helps to develop their bodies and mind.

CATS: both Unity and Peace interacted well with cats.

HOUSE TRAINING: They are trying real hard like a two year old child to remember where the poopy goes, and with patience and continued training, they will be successful!

Playful, well balanced in that they are not overly timid or assertive---just right there in the middle regarding temperament and behavior.


*.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  

We do not complete DNA tests on our rescued pups. If we do not know who the mom or dad is for sure, we guess; we use Gozer, a iPhone dog breed identifier. And, we look at their paws, ears, snout, coloring, and body build. Sometimes we are not spot on. And, remember too that even if you know the supposed dominant breed in your new puppy or adult dog, it does not mean that those particular genes will dominate your dog's personality. :)

APPLICATIONS ARE ONLINE @ karmicrescue.org

animal.description:
Meet Kai!

He is a one year old husky mix, around 50lbs.

Kai had his alteration and is all current on vaccines and microchipped!

I'm hoping his furrever family will find him soon because he deserves all the love and stability (as do all our lucky pups). He's a sweet boy- just needs someone to understand that huskies have spunk and require patience and lots of activity. Has some bad manners we are working on but over all a good boy. He is a typical high energy husky!

Kai has bloomed in his loving foster homes! When he came to LPR, he was very timid, didn't understand how to play, and wasn't really confident. Today, he is so playful, cuddly, loves to give kisses, has confidence and a spunky personality (per typical for a husky).

He is crate trained and house broken. He will need a home with a fenced in yard (6' privacy) and with husky experience.

His adoption fee is $250

We require a home visit and vet reference.

animal.description: Duke's tail is always wagging as he is happy and proud. He is proud because he was a great student in school and is back at his foster home. He worked on his basic commands and his impulse control.  Although he still wants all the human attention he can possibly get, he has learned that barreling through anything or anyone to get it is not polite.  Duke spent 9 years on a chain, but holds no grudges. All he wants is to please his people.  Housebreaking is going well and Duke is being more respectful of the elderly dog in his foster home. He has also been working on off-leash activities which is going very well. Toby came to Homes Fur Hounds after his owner passed away. He is a 2 year old Chihuahua/Dachshund mix.

Toby is very timid and afraid of his own shadow. He is frightened of noises such as a dryer, car horn, garbage disposal, people talking outside the door, the shower curtain closing, etc. 

He was wonderful with his owner, and is now loving and friendly with his foster mom, but he is still frightened of everyone else. He did try to nip at the vet tech initially but did eventually allow them to work with him and he warmed up a little. He just does not trust people. He does bark at people and other dogs when out walking.

Toby would do well with an young retiree or a family with no children where one member of the family is home a lot. He will need love and patience to teach him how to trust. He would not do well in an apartment due to all the noise and his barking at all the noise.

He is up to date on vaccines, HW negative and neutered.  For an application go to www.homesfurhounds.com. He is located in Williamsburg, Va.

Lydia is a 70lb Pointer mix who was abandoned by her family when they moved out of their house.     They literally took all of their possessions and furniture and left Lydia there, alone in an empty house.     Because of this, we don't have any prior home history.  Our vet is estimating Lydia to be around 2 years old.  

Lydia is a sweet girl who loves attention and loves to sleep with you.  She gets along good with other dogs.   She is currently living with dogs from 20 pounds to 70 pounds and has done well.    Lydia is housetrained too.   She doesn't bark much, but will let you know if she sees or hears something outside, and if someone is at the door.  

Lydia is very strong on a leash, and will not be a dog that most children can handle on leash until she has some additional training to reduce her pulling.   For this reason, Lydia is recommended for a fenced in yard, so she can run and get some of her energy out without having to be on leash.  She currently has a 6 foot privacy fence in her foster home.  She is able to jump a small 3 foot fence, so it is unknown whether she would be able to jump a 4 foot fence.  Five foot or six foot fencing is preferred.  

Lydia can go into a kennel but she will bark and would prefer a home where eventually she could have free roam.  She can be a bit mouthy or jumpy if people try to play rough with her and get her riled up.  She can be sensitive around her neck and does not like being grabbed by her collar - this has improved over the time that she has been in her foster home.  The best recommendation would be a home with older children who can respect Lydia's space. 

Adoption fee is $350.00 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact: Katie -  605-695-5126 (text preferred) or krkallemeyn@hotmail.com

This dog will be at our adoption event at the Woodbury PetSmart on Saturday from 11-2 looking for a home!


Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

animal.description:
Please note that due the volume of applications, we are unable to respond to all applicants and ONLY those being considered will be contacted. We thank you for your understanding. The adoption application link is posted below and the adoption process is outlined on the website.  Animatch asks that you read the Adoptee’s bio in its entirety before applying to ensure you meet the requirements for the dog.

Glacier is a gentle and sweet free spirit.  On the day that she was to travel to Animatch with her 7 puppies, she broke out of her travel crate and escaped.  Four days later she arrived at the Animatch Centre (after another unsuccessful escape) to join her pups.  Glacier is not accustomed to being confined (whether it be a crate or a room) and becomes stressed when she is.  In fact, she demolished part of a wall and molding around the door her first night at the Centre.  It is difficult for our Northern dogs to be free to roam one day and be restricted the next.  Despite her desire to be free, Glacier absolutely adores human companionship.  In fact, if she is outdoors alone her goal is to jump the fence; if she outdoors with a human, Glacier is right by your side asking for kisses and belly rubs.  Animatch expects that whoever adopts Glacier will be totally committed to providing her with a lifestyle that meets her needs – human presence a good part of the day, a property that is safe and secure, a love of the outdoors (especially in winter).  There is the possibility that Glacier may need medication to help with her anxiety – time will tell.  Her visit to our Vet revealed an old fracture to her hind leg.  As a result, her leg a little crooked and although she may not ever be a candidate to participate in the Iditarod, she will certainly enjoy many long walks and adventures with her human.  No doubt that Glacier will make her human the center of her universe; her life will revolve around their love, training, patience, and consistency.  If you have the experience and the desire to help Glacier through this uncertain time, you will never find a more loyal friend.  Fill in the Adoption Form and ask for Glacier.
	
Breed:  Nordic mix	
Size:	  Large (50 lbs)	
Age:	  1,5 years	
Gender:	Female
Energy:	Medium-High
Grooming:	Low	
Dog friendly:	Yes
Cat friendly:	No
Children:	8 and over

TO APPLY FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE VISIT OUR WEB SITE: www.animatch.ca AND FILL THE APPLICATION ON LINE.
*** calls and e-mails will not be answered  ***

animal.description:
Meet Scarlett!

Hey there, my name is Scarlett. I'm 10 years old and weigh 80 pounds. Yes, it's true, I'm quite a big girl. A gentle giant if you wish, because I truly am gentle. I'm fully housetrained and know how to use a doggy door, but I can't control my bladder elimination anymore, so I dribble. I'm not super fond of wearing a diaper, but if it means I get to be close to my people, I will wear one! At my foster home I lay on a washable pee pad, or on a towel to catch my dribbles. I'm a pretty laid back lady these days, so it's easier to keep me in one spot than it would be a younger, more active dog. Im pretty indifferent about cats, so I could live with them, but I wouldn't have to. I also like other dogs, specifically large dogs like me. I live with some other dogs here, but I haven't been around any children yet. I really do love my adult people the most and just want to be around them. 

I'm not too incredibly active these days. Car rides and belly rubs are some of my favorite activities. I also really enjoy the water and going swimming, but let's be real, do you know a labrador who doesn't like swimming? I'm well behaved and don't jump up on people or furniture. I'm pretty fond of relaxing in the sun outside when it's nice out. I'm a perfect girl in my crate, and don't mind being in there when you have to leave, and I'm even more perfect when you come home and I get to be by you! I'm hoping my new human will love me for who I am and be by my side every step of the way, and in return I will show them all of my devotion.

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
Meet George Michael! 

Here are some great things his foster mom has to say about Georgie:
“I had a 10 year span of experience in the canine industry as a dog groomer and vet tech and this dog is hands-down the smartest dog I have gotten to know. I have never met a dog so enthusiastic about pleasing his people; he loves to work and he would love to have a job. He is so smart, eager and fast that I could easily see him as an agility, flyball, nosework, tracking or rally obedience star. This dog is up for anything you want to do! 
He is fearful of strangers and takes a while to warm up to people. It does take him a while to fully trust somebody but once he does, he is so much fun to be around. He is quicker to warm up to women rather than men. A dog savvy and experienced home without cats or small children would suit him the best. 
He loves to play ball and flirt pole. He is also good at amusing himself if you are busy and will toss the ball around by himself. He will also avidly watch tv if there are animals on it. He very much thrives on routine and if he has a set schedule he will stick to it without complaint. He is not destructive (except for tennis balls) and will never have an accident in the house for any reason. 
He is a gorgeous dog and people comment on him wherever we go. Most people like to tell me that he looks like a dingo. He is a very interesting-looking dog and he is so adorable that he makes my heart melt. Everyone that lays eyes on him becomes enamored. 
He isn’t a lap-dog but wants to always be near his people. He can be goofy and cuddly but he also likes to do his own thing.” 

Georgie would love a home with someone who worked from home and was able to spend a lot of time with him. He’s made many improvements thanks to the help of his amazing foster mom, and our trainer, so that he can be the very best boy for his new forever family. His ideal forever home will work on Georgie’s success with continued work with either our trainer, or a trainer nearby to their home. He would love being able to do agility and work/have a job as he is happiest when he is able to have a job. 

To adopt George Michael Aka Georgie, visit our website for an adoption application!
Thegratefuldogrescue.org

animal.description:
Blanca got to go on a Dogs Day Out and here's what the volunteer said about their time: 



Blanca loved going for a car ride! She hopped right in and enjoyed looking out the window. It was a bit chilly out, but not too cold for a walk around the park. She didn't mind the leash and walked fairly well. Her back leg is a little weaker, but it didn't stop her from having a good time, and she could walk just fine. We were fortunate enough to even see some ducks. Blanca wasn't nervous, though they seemed to confuse her a little! I also found out that Blanca loves to be petted, and is very affectionate when you kneel down to her level! After the park, she was happy to jump back in the car and quickly curled up on the seat to relax. Overall, she is a very sweet girl and did not appear to be nervous with any people or animals that we saw from a distance. I enjoyed spending a day with Blanca very much!

 I've learned to ignore cats andI love my canine fostersisters! Although, one of them thinks I play a littleroughsometimes.

Meet Gypsy and Tyson! They are a ‘pittie wonderful’ bonded pair who must be adopted together. Their hearts would simply shatter if they were separated. Both are under the care of our friends at the Manchester Animal Shelter in Manchester, NH. They are spay/neutered and up to date on vaccinations. 

Tyson, the gentleman, who is a brown 5-year old, 75-pound male pittie mix. Tyson is a calm, gentle lover. He likes the quieter, finer things in life: a nice walk, a snuggle on the couch watching TV, a nice massage ;)...He can be quite silly, too, and is a blast to play with!

Then there's Gypsy is the lady of the pair. She’s a white, 12-year old, 65-pound female pittie mix. Gypsy is a spunky gal who is still full of life and energy! She's a go-getter! She loves life and everything it has to offer. She's very social and loves to know everything that's going on. :) She is the more independent one of the two.

These two cuties have been together since Tyson was born. They had two loving owners, but both of them sadly passed away late in 2020. Now they are on their own, waiting for a new home with humans to love and care for them. Rest assured, they want to love and take care of you, too.  
Complete your family with these special fur kids! They would do best in a home with children 12+ years old. For an application, please email  canines@manchesteranimalshelter.org Be sure to tell them ARK sent you! #ARKforGypsyandTyson  #JustSaveThem

animal.description:
This beautiful little pocket Pittie princess is looking for a special home of her own.

Sophia is approximately 4 years old, and 50 pounds. She is short, stocky, and straight adorable. She loves to snuggle under her blankets, and is a loyal, loving sweetheart toward her humans. She is friendly with other large, submissive dogs, and would do well sharing her home with another confident dog. 
Sophia has had a hard life. She came from a terrible home, was fearful, and had heartworm that we treated her for. She is all healthy now, and waiting for her forever family. Sophia can be nervous of new people, and is not a fan of kids unpredictable movements and behaviors. She would thrive in a quiet home with no children and little to no visitors. She would be the perfect companion for a retired couple looking for a sweet girl to give them warm and loving company. 

To adopt Sophia, visit our website for an application
Thegratefuldogrescue.org

animal.description:
Rosie Posie is headed to the PNW and so excited to meet her furever hooman/s! This sweet girl has waited a very long time for this moment. She was found as a stray with an embedded collar and not in the best shape, but look at her now!! Her name is Rosie from her incredibly rosey, happy personality but also references the beautiful pink undertone she has. She is what we like to refer to as a pocket pittie-- the beautiful features of a pittie, in miniature! She is estimated at 1 yr old and weighs rougly under 40 lbs-- a perfect size pup to take with you everwhere you go.....and she would love that! She loves car rides, walks, meeting new people and other dogs. She can be a little timid around strangers and sometimes give out a low "woof" if she feels uncomfortable, but Rosie is such a great girl and her attention can very easily be redirected. Her fosters have been amazing at helping to care for her skin wounds and allow her time to heal both inside and out. She is fostered with another young female dog, who she gets along with so well....Rosie loves other dogs! She loves to go on walks and to run around doing zoomies. She enjoys bath time and absolutely loves peanut butter. She is not shy to catch a spot on the couch and will give you kisses galore, if allowed. This sweet girl is special and cannot wait to meet her very special hooman/s. 

To bring Rosie Posie home, please apply here-
https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/19764/generic or email cynthia@threelittlepittiesrescue.org if you have an application on file.

The adoption fee is $500 and includes all vaccines (DHPP & booster, Bordatella, Rabies), spay/neuter, microchip, multiple dewormings, flea preventative, heartworm treatment with 6 months of heartworm preventative for after adoption, a high quality nylon Martingale collar, a 30 day trial of pet insurance, transport from TX to the PNW, and many years of priceless memories.

**APPLICATION REQUIRED FOR A RESPONSE**

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Bonnie Belle, and I came into Cuz i Matter Animal Rescue on 12/18/2020.  I am a 4 year old female Shepherd/Terrier Mix who my foster mom says I weigh about 30 pounds, have the softest fur, and the most expressive eyes you've ever seen.  I fit into my foster home with no trouble at all.  There are 3 other dogs here, and I get along with all of them.  There's a cat here too, and while I ignore her most of the time, it's hard to resist chasing her when she runs.  

I did test positive for heartworm so will need to receive treatment - Cuz i Matter Animal Rescue will continue to pay for that even if you adopt me, but it is important for me, and for all dogs, to be on a heartworm preventative.

I am housetrained, crate trained, walk well on a leash, and love to jump in the car and go for a ride.  I like squeaky toys a lot, too!  I don't bark very much -- not even when the other dogs here are howling at the FedEx truck or at the people talking on foster mom's Zoom meetings.  I'm pretty much perfect!  I like running around outside and sunbathing a little each day, but mostly I like hanging out with my people in the house.  Snuggle-time on the couch is the best!  I could be happy living in an apartment with some regular time outside, or I could be happy in a house with my own yard.  I am an easy-going, good, sweet girl.  I promise to come running from across the house to jump in your lap and give you kisses when I see you sit on the couch, and then you can pet my belly, okay?

If you'd like more information about me, please send CiMAR an email so they can send you all the information about adopting me.  You can also find more pictures of me on their website:  http://www.cuzimatter.org/adopt-a-dog

animal.description:
**WE ONLY DO HOME VISITS FOR ADOPTIONS NEAR BROWARD & PALM BEACH COUNTIES**

Ooh la laa laaa Xavier Pekingese is prancing into your heart! He's 7 years old and needs to put on some weight so he will be around 12+ pounds. He needs an adult home, preferably as an only dog because he is learning not to be possessive of his toys. He is respectful of humans and his toys but he would NOT be good with children. He is doing well with respecting his foster dogs and his toys but this is something that would need a dedicated calm person the continue to help him with if you have another small dog. Xavier needs a home with a routine and people that will approach him slowly. He responds well to baby talk and lowering yourself to his level and not standing over him. Once he trusts he will not be hit by you he is kissy and loving! When you tell him he is a good boy he wags his fluffy tail with excitement! He will need basic grooming and monthly heartworm prevention as all dogs in Florida should be on because of mosquitos spreading Heartworm disease. Xavier also had a dental cleaning with his vetting. This dog's adoption fee is $350 to go towards their vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, and microchip as well as grooming if needed). If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check our FAQ's Page. 

 *All dogs in the care of Get a Life Pet Rescue live in loving foster homes while waiting for their perfect match. They don't live in cages or crates (unless there is a medical reason to do so.) They are treated as family pets while in our care. * All dogs in our care are fed premium brand holistic food as well as supplements and vitamins specific to each dog's needs. We don't buy inexpensive bulk dry kibble, our rescues are fed premium wet food diets as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program to ensure maximum health.*All of our rescues receive complete quality vetting including full dental cleaning with pre-op bloodwork, spay/neuter, vaccines, and grooming. Dogs in need of specialized medicine will be seen by specialists, such as full cardiac workups, ophthalmologist visits, all suspicious lumps, and bumps are biopsied, and every medical need is transparent to potential adopters. *Once you adopt from Get a Life Pet Rescue, you become part of our compassionate family and we are here for you if a problem with your precious dog arises.

animal.description:
If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com



****Please read the entire bio before inquiring.   Google is not recommended to  diagnose heart conditions or possible concerns versus speaking to a licensed veterinarian****

Chinook is a 3-4 month old husky pup that came to us in December.  He was surrendered from a breeder due to him having concerns with his heart.     Chinook's heart murmur was confirmed, and then we had an echocardiagram done on him to look into it further.   Chinook has two somewhat leaky valves that are causing the murmur.  All of his other heart measurements were normal and no meds are currently needed & he currently has no restrictions.   He was cleared for anesthesia and is ready to look for a family to call his own.    Another echocardiagram is recommended for Chinook in 3-4 months to recheck his heart, and see if there are any changes with his growth. Doctors feel there is a small chance of continued improvement in his murmur as he grows and he should be able to have a long and healthy life.     

Chinook needs a family that understands that there may not be further issues down the road, but there also might be.  His adoptive family needs to be prepared to care for him in any way that he needs as he ages.    Please consult the vet that would be caring for Chinook if adopted if you have questions about what could be concerns. 

Chinook is your typical husky pup.  He likes to try to take things from the adult dogs, and all he wants is to eat and play with toys and other dogs.  He can be a talker and is still working on his housetraining.  He is sleeping in a crate at night and when his foster is gone and he is doing well, but not 100% there yet.  Chinook does have some puppy pad training as well.   He is currently living with a 6 foot wood privacy fence.   He currently weighs around 30 lbs and will be 60lbs+ full grown. 

Preference given to applications with  6 foot fenced yards and prior husky breed experience.    Huskies are escape artists and not recommended with cats.  They are runners if they get off leash.  

Adoption fee is $450.00 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact: Katie -  kit_n_caboodle22@hotmail.com

This dog will be at our adoption event at the Woodbury PetSmart on Saturday from 11-2 looking for a home! 

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

animal.description:
The copper colored beautiful boy is 5 year old Redd!

Redd just came to Manhattan and is settling in and making great friends with the Bideawee staff. He's an absolute sweetheart, running from person to person for pets, affection, and his all time favorite, belly rubs. 

Redd is not a fan of other dogs and likes to let them know how he feels by barking, which isn't always great on a walk. We are looking for a patient owner who will help him with these manners, and with some training tips he has improved in the past. He'll do much better in a loving home than he will in the shelter where he's surrounded by other pups, which is super stressful for him. 

Redd is a great boy who will always be there for pets and kisses, and he'll always be happy as long as you're around. 

Redd is looking for an adult only home where he's the only furball in the home. If you're interested in this cutie, you must click "Apply for Adoption" to submit an online application.

If you're viewing this animal on Petfinder, please visit the animal's page on Bideawee.org and click on the "Apply for Adoption" button to submit an adoption application!

animal.description:
Maggie is a very special, pure breed girl. She is registered with the American Kennel Club and used to compete in field trials, but now she is retired. Unfortunately her previous owner became too sick to take care of her and two other Beagles, so the family asked BRSM for help. Maggie is a very sweet and easy going girl with a velvety soft coat. She enjoys the company of other dogs and shows no food aggression or other. She also does not mind that her foster brother wants to be no. 1 and keeps photo bombing her pictures or gives her sloppy kisses. She is just a real patient sweetheart who likes taking things slow, sniff around and get some pets and belly rubs, and of course like all Beagles, she likes a good meal. Maggie will probably also be happy to be the only dog in the house since she is not interested in playing at this point but she is still new so things may change.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Marcela! I was rescued in Puerto Rico while I was pregnant with my litter of puppies and brought to the Big Dog Ranch Rescue to give birth comfortably. I gave birth to 4 beautiful puppies here on the ranch. I am a very sweet girl and can be a little clingy with the humans that I get attached to, but that just means that I love you! I'm pretty mellow and overall a great dog that would make an excellent pet for any owner. I would prefer to be the only dog in my future home, as I am typically not a fan of interacting with other dogs. I don't appear to respond to a high prey drive, but proceed with caution if you have a feline friend in your home. I would be happy living in any type of environment, as I am very adaptable and calm. I am very friendly when I meet new visitors and I think I would love to join you out and about in public if you'll take me. I am well-trained and appear to be potty-trained, as I never go to the bathroom inside. I love to go for long leashed walks, play with toys, and most of all, snuggle on the couch next to someone that I love!

animal.description:
1/17/2021-
Please thoroughly read the bio before applying and note, he is not considered hypoallergenic.

Rusty, one of the cutest dogs you’ll ever see. Originally thought to be around 5 years old(seems younger at heart) Shih Tzu mix(Foster Mom calls him a fancy foo foo breed)is looking for his special adopter.

Many factors and time go into fostering a dog that needed to be brought back from the brink of death. He was abandoned, locked in a crate, thrown in a portapot left to starve to death, which he nearly did. His road to recovery started in Georgia with his first foster Mom, Kristin. The personality of a dog at first isn't the personality that emerges over time once they are rehabilitated from their medical conditions. After being in foster here in PA for months now , his current foster Mom Cindy has truly been learning the little one's real personality. He discovers new happiness everyday as we help him with manners.

Rusty is a loving and sweet pup. He is a not so innocent pup who sees things so innocently. He LOVES his people. So far all the people he has come in contact with he smiles and of course with a face like his...you can’t help but smile back. He is feisty though, very feisty and energetic. Seems to be making up and moving on from his horrible past.
He likes to be by your side which also means he is under foot a bit. 
He is just about housetrained BUT isn't 100% there yet. He can be very vocal and likes to join in conversation or start them up himself should he feel he’s not getting your full attention. 

He LOVES to play with dogs HOWEVER he is very in your face and needs to be compatible with the potential adopter's dog who is tolerant of that rambunctious behavior. 

He was VERY curious with the resident cat HOWEVER that curiosity turned into an obsession to bite the cat's tail. The resident cat truly holds his own BUT this would now put Rusty in a potential forever home with NO cats.

Rusty is very mouthy but luckily his adorable underbite seems to prevents pain from being inflicted which is why a household consisting of children under 12 is not recommended. 

Adopter must live within less than a 50 mile radius of the rescue he is with. (Horsham PA area).

SO , if you think you are the perfect home and meet with the above criteria for this little man please complete an application and his foster Mom will be happy to talk with prospected approved applicants.


To begin the adoption process please, fill out our online application. Go to wagsrescue.com and click on adoption form.
Please call Susan @ 267-312-3372 if you have any general questions.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Dena at DenaE@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Puddy
Estimated Breed : Great Dane Mastiff Mix
Approximate Age: 6 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 100 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Puddy is a sweet, gentle giant. He will need a home with plenty of room to stretch his long legs as well as a family without small children that can be accidentally knocked down. Puddy has lots of love to give and hopes to find his forever home in the country where he has lots of room to safely roam in a large fenced yard. He's great with other dogs, but it was reported to us not good with cats. We can't be sure if he is housetrained so expect some possible work in that area. While Puddy is dog friendly, he'd do best as only dog in the home. He loves to just lounge around and get all the love.

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
**Due to high volume in rescue adoptions Treasured Animal Rescue highly recommends and adoption application be completed - link below.**

Hello, my name is Daisy and I am 1 1/2 years young.  I am a terrier mix but my foster mom tells me that I am one of the greatest breeds on earth, a Great American Mutt!  I am very proud of that. I am a small girl and weigh 28lbs but I will probably weigh less. 
I was found down south as a stray. I was waiting for my babies to arrive.  My rescue angels thought they had time so they told me: "Daisy, we have plenty of time to get you up north to Chicago!".  Well..... surprise!  I had my babies very shortly after arriving in IL.  
My babies are all healthy and well on their way so it is time for me to enjoy a little "me" time. 
I was a naughty girl. I am an escape artist and I ran away from my foster home and stayed away from 6 weeks until I came back. I am glad I am back because it was very cold out there and I was getting very hungry   My foster mom was very, very, very mad at me and scolded me. 
 My foster mom says that I am a lovebug.  She calls me her velcro because once I get attached to her I won't leave!   There is also a 1 year young boy here and I just love being with him. I don't like to see him cry so I stay by his side. That seems to cam him down. 
My foster mom tells me I am her best pillow because I love sleeping at the top of her bed!   
I can wait to meet my forever family. I haven't had the best life but I am loving my new life. They tell me that I will be going to a place where I am loved and safe and will have plenty to eat. Can we meet? 
I promise I will be by your side for the rest of my life.  
I can't wait to lay at the top of your bed, for me that's the best place in the whole wide world!

To meet Daisy please complete an adoption application at www.treasuredanimalrescueinc.org 
We cannot adopt out of the state of IL 

We might not be able to get back to you due to the large volume of applications. Please check our website for updates on the adoption status of your pet of choice.  Thank you for choosing to adopt.

animal.description: The Taffy pups will bring a little sweetness into your life! These adorable fluff balls look to be little Australian Shepherd mixes with cute bob tails. We aren't sure who their dad is, what their exact mix is or how big they will get but Mama Taffy is around 40 lbs so we expect these pups to be medium to large when they are done growing. Chewy is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. We require all puppy adopters to provide training that includes: house training, basic training, leash training, and socialization. Additionally, this cutie is going to need proper exercise, mental stimulation, and your attention and love to grow up to be the best companion. We do not allow our dogs or puppies to sleep or live outside; they must be incorporated into your family and be made a priority in your life. animal.description:
Hello!! My name is Zeke, and I just arrived at Stray Haven! I came all the way from North Carolina. The caretakers here think that I'm a coooool guy. I have swag. I am only 4 years old and sometimes live in my own world. I've been around the block in my four years though. The first thing you might notice about me is that I only have one good eye. My other one was injured somehow and my body took care of it. But that doesn't slow me down! (Although, I'm known for walking into glass doors). I have a couple other lumps and bumps on me, but right now I seem to have a clean bill of health! I'm pretty good with other dogs as long as they are not in my face, I like to keep to myself. I'm a typical hound, who keeps my nose to the ground doing my own thing. But I'll come back to you for some pets every once in a while. I'm pretty much housetrained too, but hey sometimes accidents happen here in the kennel. I'm sure I'll do a lot better in a home. Once I am in a home, I could benefit from some crate training though. Sometimes when I'm alone in the yard I can get into trouble! I'm just a curious guy. If you are interested, stop into Stray Haven and meet the coolest guy on the block -- Zeke!
Stray Haven Humane Society & SPCA
194 Shepard Rd., Waverly, NY 14892
(607) 565-2859, www.strayhavenspca.org 
Open hours (winter): Tues, Wed & Thurs Noon - 6pm; Sat 10am-4pm

animal.description:
Sachi

Arriving in Denver 1/17/21

Chihuahua mix

9 months old

Doesn't love other dogs, does ok with those that mind their own business after a slow introduction 

No idea on cats 

Would do great with kids who are old enough to understand she's a little unique and needs to be treated like the princess she is 

House trained

Crate trained and she doesn't know much other than her name as far as commands go 

Prefers bottled water (don't even ask) 

Will need to stay on supplements 

Must stay a trim and healthy weight 

MAY need a cart in the very distant future

Loves to wear clothes 

All about cuddling and attention

Up to date on everything besides needing to be spayed which will be done in early February 

10lbs approx

Sachi's story is lifetime movie devastating. She was abandoned with her mom by her owners right before Christmas. They said they were surrendering them because Sachi couldn't walk and the 2 dogs were bonded so they couldn't just surrender her. She was confused as was her mom and with her needing vet care, her future was looking grim. Once at the foster home we noticed a couple things, 1 Sachi could in fact walk and run & 2 her momma Aria was REALLY sick. When we got Sachi to the vet we were sad to find out that she was born without any hips. So when the owner said "she's been like this for a while,"@ I guess they meant her entire freaking life! What stinks is had they taken her to the vet early on she could have had 2 FHO surgeries to "correct" it. Unfortunately now the scar tissue is immense and her muscles have atrophied, so it's no longer an option. Our choices were to amputate both her rear legs, which seemed unnecessary being she uses them in her own way, or to leave her and understand she will need to stay on supplements and pain meds, must stay a healthy weight, and in the future may need a cart and pain management.

While it's upsetting that we cannot correct her rear leg issues it has been amazing to watch her blossom in her foster home and truly become the charismatic little diva she deserves to be. Momma Aria's future wasn't to be as hopeful. We fought with Aria, (our vet bills prove it), but despite everything we did treatment wise the years of neglect took their toll. At approx 6:00 am on Jan 6th Aria took her last breath, asleep and cuddled with Sachi, it was peaceful but absolutely heartbreaking. While we are devastated at this loss we find comfort in knowing that Aria FINALLY knew her last baby was safe and loved, she was able to peacefully leave the epic mess that was her body in the most dignified way, as she deserved. 

This sweet girl is only 9 months old and has experienced so much loss and neglect. She lost her human family, her home, her momma and now she is headed to us happier and hopefully. We are sure that her happy FURever after home and family are waiting for her arrival with great anticipation. 

If you believe this fantastic family is in fact YOU please contact us ASAP!

Original Post

https://www.facebook.com/100007204158922/posts/2779103145673130/?d=n

 $250.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our VOICEMAIL at (402)957-1578

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!
