Is this dog Housebroken?...  Advice from a veterinarian:  Even if a dog is housebroken at my house, it does not mean that it understands not to pee at someone else's house.  It ONLY understands not to pee at my house.  Some dogs make the connection that they should only pee outside.  Some must be retrained when they come home.  All we can tell you for sure is whether/or not a dog's crate is clean when we come to walk them in the AM.  All this means is that they are crate trained and waited to pee until we took them outside.

What is this dog's Temperament?...  We do not have a clear picture of a dog's temperament until we have allowed them to settle in for a few days.  Even then they are living in a shelter environment with many other dogs and a lot of daily activity.  It can be difficult to say a dog is "calm" or "nervous" when the shelter environment is playing a big role in that behavior.  We only rescue FRIENDLY dogs who have no known bite history.  If a dog is at Small Miracles, it likes people and has a good temperament.  We always suggest you meet the dog to see if it is the right fit for your lifestyle. 

What are your Fees?...  Base adoption fee is $325 for adult dogs and puppies.  To this, we add a $30 microchip fee, which we register for you, and a 6 month supply of heartworm preventative.  Heartworm preventative costs $40-60 depending on the weight of the dog.  This means that a large dog will total $405.00 and an extra large dog will total $415.00.

Why can't I adopt a FREE dog?...  Our adoption fee covers many procedures which cost much more for us then the amount we ask for from you. We spay/neuter all pets, and we give them their first round of vaccines (canine distemper, bordatella, Rabies if age appropriate).  At a typical vet clinic this would cost you $500 at minimum for the surgery, and each vaccine is roughly $35 each.  Even if your adopted dog does not have all of its shots due to the mandatory waiting period between booster shots, we offer vaccinations at the low cost of $20/shot.  We test all dogs for heartworm disease and tickborn illnesses such as Lymes.  We never euthanize a heartworm positive dog, and treatment routinely costs us $3000/dog.  We collect a fecal sample from every rescued dog and run a microscopic parasite test.  Any parasites found will be treated with two rounds of the appropriate dewormer.  We treat all dogs for fleas and ticks with Advantage.  If a dog has significant dental disease or "very dirty teeth", we will perform a dental cleaning when the dog has its spay/neuter surgery.  A dental cleaning with extractions would cost you upwards of $400-600 at your local vet clinic.

ALSO NOTE... Small Miracle is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization.  We survive off of our adoption fees and donations from the community.  We are a non-profit animal rescue and do not receive income from tax revenue as some county shelters do. 

For more information including Adoption Hours and Rescue Address, please visit our website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org

*Due to concerns surrounding COVID-19, we have reformatted the way that we do adoptions in order to follow social distancing protocols. We are thrilled that so many people want to adopt right now, but we are not equipped to handle the large number of calls, applications, and email inquiries we are receiving. We are no longer answering phone calls and are doing all communications with adopters via email. If you have a dog you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application before sending us emails. When your application has been processed, you will receive an email from us with further instructions on how to adopt. You do not need a new application for every dog that you are interested in adopting. 

At MAMCO we understand that in order to continue rescuing moms and babies, we must stretch our finances as far as we are able. For this reason we use variable adoption pricing. By assigning higher adoption fees to high demand moms and puppies, we are able to rescue more families in need.The money raised through these adoptions acts as a benefactor to moms and puppies in our care who require expensive veterinary treatments, have behavioral issues, or need more time to find a home. We often reduce the adoption fees on these harder-to-place moms and puppies to help them find forever families. Adoption fees vary, but all include spay or neuter, microchip, up to date vaccinations and deworming, rabies vaccine at the time of spay or neuter, and 30 days of pet insurance. We also cover hernia repair and cherry eye repair at the time of spay or neuter. Applications can be filled out at mamcorescue.org.

animal.description:
When Kody joined Rescue Row in the beginning of December, his skin was red, raw and itchy, his feet were swollen, and he had horrible ear infections. He is now ready to find his forever home! This is what his foster mom has to say about him: Kody had an injury to his front leg when he was younger which healed incorrectly, but it doesnt bother him and doesnt stop him from playing! He loves playing with my dogs and would love a doggy sibling in his new home. No small children because he could knock them over with his zoomies. He is house broken, non-destructive, kennels easily with a treat and I only kennel him when I leave the house. He can be shy with strangers at first, walks well on a leash, and he still takes Apoquel every day and gets a medicated bath once a week. He attaches to his person and rarely barks. He is such a sweet guy!

If you would like to adopt a dog from Rescue Row please fill out an application at https://form.jotform.com/91767055990166 

*Please check your junk email folder if you do not receive a response from a Rescue Row member within 48 hours.

*You must live within an hour of the DFW Metroplex because we do trial adoptions and require a homecheck

*Our adoption fees are as follows (paid by cash or a check made out to Rescue Row):

 Dogs 12 weeks-6 months old: $300 adoption fee

 Dogs 7 months and older: $275 adoption fee

Rescue Row is a 501(c)3 (non-profit) all volunteer dog rescue organization serving the DFW Metroplex. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations, and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances. We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs.

animal.description:
Lola Lu- female
Breed: Shepherd mix
Estimated age: 1-2 years old
Weight: just under 60lbs

Currently Seeking:
- A very patient home - I was brought to the rescue after having minimal interaction with humans and a lack of socialization, so a lot of things are scary. I've come a long way in my time in rescue but I still need a patient home
- A home with another DOG - I feel more comfortable and confident in the world with another friend and I may even want to play
- A home with older children - because I am a nervous girl I need a home with a family to give me space and patience to open up
- A home with plenty of yummy treats! I am a food motivated gal who loves all things food
- A home with comfy beds and blankets to snooze in
- A home with a fenced in yard

***Lola Lu needs a very patient home. She was brought into the rescue near feral and very fearful of people and her surroundings. She is not a dog that is going to immediately gravitate to you/ask for attention/snuggle you, and currently she can only be pet on her terms. Given the time and space she needs she will open up, but it will take time! But they do say the best things in life don't come easy 


Before emailing- please read:
- Yes, this dog is available for adoption
- The adoption fee for Lola Lu is $256
- Apply at c2cnd.org
- The adoption fee covers their age appropriate shots, microchip, deworming, spay/neuter, and any other medical expenses while in our care.
- Local adopters only. Due to our thorough adoption process including home visits, we limit our adoptions to local families in the greater Charlotte area.
- If you have any additional questions, email us at dogs@c2cnd.org and we will respond as soon as possible!

Want a real sweetie for a best buddy?  TJ is your girl.  TJ is a one year old Terrier mix.  She weighs 16 pounds.  TJ is spayed, heartwood negative and on a preventative, microchipped and current on all vaccinations.

TJ is an active girl who will always be ready for a good romp in the backyard or a couple of miles on the Hike and Bike Trail.  She would be perfect for an active family with older kids.  

TJ needs to be the only dog in the home.  She does not get along with other dogs.  

TJ is making real progress on house training.  She is crate trained.  

Adoption fee $400
** The Texas Comptroller now requires sales tax on adoption fees.

** Temporarily Suspended due to COVID **
Monthly Meet & Greets  (12:00 - 2:00)
Petco (in Leander) every 1st Saturday of the month
Pet Supplies Plus (Parmer & Mopac) every third Saturday of the month


** Please note: Due to their size, our dogs are not suitable for homes with children under 5..

We do not have a facility, all dogs are fostered in the homes of our volunteers. If you are interested in adopting a dog from Lil' Paws Maltese Rescue and other Petite Paws, please visit our website at www.lilpaws-malteserescue.org and fill out an adoption application. This is the first step in our adoption process. Our goal is to place our dogs in safe, stable and loving homes in the Austin Metropolitan area. Thanks for looking!

Lil' Paws Maltese Rescue and other Petite Paws depends on donations to keep the dogs in our program healthy. Many health issues are taken care of before a dog leaves a rescue: spaying, neutering, immunizations, dental care, and in some cases major surgery. Because of the cost of this care, donations are essential to enable us to continue our work. If you would like to show appreciation for what we do and help us continue to do it please go to our website homepage and click the donate button. We thank you in advance for your support.

animal.description:
Please contact JoEllen (sagdinfo@aol.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Nate is a handsome 3-month-old Terrier blend who weighs approximately 15 pounds. He initially is shy but quickly warms up when shown kindness. He has a sweet temperament and is active and playful. He will make a loyal companion.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for his entire life (up to 15+ years or more) - not just until his puppy cuteness wears off.
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization. Like most puppies, he may chew on anything within his reach to include but not limited to baseboards, shoes, socks, children's toys, electrical cords, plants, etc.
His adoption fee is $250. This includes his neuter surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccinations, Bravecto, Drontal Plus, Tri-Heart Plus Chewable Tablet, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.

Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved and you are traveling from out-of-town, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Sweet Nikki falls in love with everyone she meets and with her great demeanor she will steal your heart.  Nikki is a one-year-old 30-ish pound hound mix, energetic and playful.  She loves to "herd" the resident foster dog in the home so she would love another canine companion so she can hone her skills!  A fenced yard will be ideal for her.   Nike is a little "mouthy" when she plays so older kids would be best.  She does not bite nor is she "barky" 
Nikki is heartworm positive and we will have her treated in 30 days.  We do not want to hold up her adoption and so for that reason we'd like a home for her in south Jersey so she can be treated by her favorite vet next month.  As you may know, heartworm is not contagious but will require some quiet time after treatment.  
Nikki is housetrained, crate-trained, spayed and up to date with vaccinations.  She will make a great companion in any loving home where she can get her exercise in a fenced yard and take great walks with her person.   She's a love!
Applications at www.pounddogfounddog at the top of the homepage.

animal.description:
Meet Tory!

This handsome devil is an English Coonhound X Beagle. He's a chunky 5 year old dude, weighing in at about 55 pounds.

Sadly, Tory's owner surrendered him to the shelter due to a life threatening medical condition that prevented him from providing proper care. Tory has always known love. This is clear from his happy greeting of all people both young and old. He seems most happy in the company of younger people. He can be a little jumpy so caution around toddlers and younger should be used.

Tory had very little training when he came into our rescue. His leash manners needed a lot of work. He likely had not been walked on leash much before. Tory has been working very hard on his leash manners and has made great progress. His forever family will need to be realistic and committed to continued training in this regard. Tory is not the dog your small child will be able to walk.

Tory is housetrained and loves his crate. He sleeps the night away in his crate without fuss. Tory does show some resource guarding of his food bowl. For this reason he is fed in his crate. This gives him the security to know he can eat his food peacefully. It was very evident to Foster Mom that Tory may have been fed table scraps exclusively in his previous home. He is now on kibble and doing great. A strict feeding schedule with high value treats reserved only for training will be important in keeping his weight controlled.

A home with another chill and low key dog would be fine with Tory, although we suspect his happy place is as an only dog. Tory really has no interest in playing with another dog. Tory is said to have lived compatibly with cats in his previous home.

Tory LOVES to engage with people and is very vocal in his want for attention. He loves to sit on your lap and have his chest rubbed. Tory doesn't bark at the doorbell or visitors to the home. He is very vocal when he's telling you stories of his day though.

A Hound that thrives on reliable structure and a strong leader, Tory is going to do best in a home with a confident and experienced family. Tory is not a suitable "first time" dog. Having a dog in your family home when you grew up doesn't count as dog experience (sorry...)

Tory will require a fully fenced yard. We will not consider apartments or condo's for any reason.

Tory is located in Guelph, Ontario. We will be considering applications from Ontario and Quebec only at this time. Transport can be arranged.

If you are interested in chatting with our team, the first step is to complete our online application. https://www.coonhoundrescue.ca/adoption-application

Please Note:

We are all volunteers and busy taking care of our foster dogs so please take the time to fill out our on-line adoption application if you are interested in more information about any of the hounds that we have for adoption. Filling out our application does not obligate you to adopt in any way. It does, however, help us to determine if the dog that your interested in would be a good match for your family and lifestyle.

All of our dogs are fully vetted. They have been vaccinated, altered, microchipped and heartworm tested and on prevention.

VISIT COONHOUND COMPANIONS WEBSITE TO SEE WHY ADOPTING A COONHOUND CAN BE A WONDERFUL EXPERIENCE!

www.coonhoundcompanions.com

ADOPTION FEE: $450.00

LOCATION: Tory is currently in foster care in Guelph, ON. With the help of volunteers, transportation to his forever home can possibly be arranged. Don't let distance deter you!

If you would like to give this handsome boy a forever home please fill out our on line adoption application at

www.coonhoundrescue.ca/adoption-application

animal.description:
If you are interested in this dog, don't waste time with an inquiry! Fill out an application here to get the ball rolling...
https://pethavenmn.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/dog-adoption-application/

Here is more about Nellie!

Nellie is a loving and playful one-year-old, 60-pound Lab / Retriever mix. She is house-trained, does best with routine, and is still working on letting her human know when she needs to go outside. Nellie is also crate-trained but she is vocal when she is in there. When her foster dad is out, she has been okay left to roam the house along with her foster brother without issue.

Nellie has done well with children she has met, has not had exposure to cats, and with slow introductions she is coexisting with the resident dog in her foster home. She is leash reactive and does not yet recognize social cues and ends up jumping up and pestering other dogs trying to get them to play to the point where she will need to be separated. She is working on this in her foster home, and a forever home that will continue this training is important.

Nellie is a total sweetheart with her human and loves to climb up and be a lap dog, get belly rubs, play fetch for as long as you are willing, and go for long walks. She'll need a calm, patient human who can provide redirection and positive reinforcement for good behavior as she's shown a tendency for demand barking when she wants to play. A tall, fenced yard would be ideal for Nellie as she loves to run around and let out some energy! She has not shown interest in jumping the fence; however, she has shown a propensity to try to push the gates open and escape.

Nellie lives an active lifestyle and would love someone who will take her hiking or on long walks. She really will need to have a single-family home and yard to play in. It is likely she will warm up to other resident dogs eventually and would love someone who will be patient with her as she learns to socialize better, but as a constant cuddler, she would love to be an only dog and the center of attention!



Her adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

animal.description:
Pepper Joe goes by Hank now... If you are an active person who is looking for a devoted dog with a big streak of sweetness, Hank is your guy. He wants nothing more than to spend time with the person or people he loves: taking hikes, chasing the ball, going on runs and leash walks. He bonds deeply-as herding dogs will do-and is a fine mashup of Border Collie smarts and cartoon goofiness (just watch him sleep with his head half off his dog bed and his legs in the air). 

He is big energy and wants an active person or small family to help him spend that energy. But Hank also has a fine capacity for being chill: for curling up nearby while you work or read or watch TV. He loves road trips. He loves just hanging out. He doesn't seem to favor a certain type of person. In the past, Hank has bonded with an 11-year-old boy (inseparable), a 57-year-old woman (smitten), and a 30-something couple (double love). Though he is fine with small children when he's outdoors, Hank is NOT recommended for a home with small children. Hank is house trained and good with other dogs. He needs to be reminded firmly not to chase/herd cats. Our house cat is not fazed by him and often crowds Hank out of his own dog bed. 

Not every home is a good fit for Hank. He was rescued as an adult and has a particular area where he needs loving guidance. When he is inside his home, Hank can be anxious around people he doesn't know, or people who come around the people he loves, including other family members. Hank shows this anxiety with a groaning vocalization-we call it "the creaky door sound-and sometimes he adds Border Collie herding moves around the person of concern. If the behavior is not interrupted and redirected, it can escalate to barking and nipping. He doesn't do this with everyone. We've been working with a trainer to teach Hank to redirect and change this behavior and he has made very good progress at his foster home (two adults and a teenager). Hank is smart and he wants to learn. A house with a lot of visitors (say, with a home business or daycare) would not be a good fit. A house with small children would also not be a good fit.

If you can give Hank some patient training along with a kind, stable home, he will reward you. He will be about the most devoted, joyous dog you can imagine. When he sees the person he loves, Hank wags his tail so hard he nearly falls over. When he falls in love, he falls hard. A home on the quiet side and a smaller family-or even a single person-is recommended for Hank.

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.
